web.archive.org/web/20190721161531/https://www.delta.com/us/en/about-delta/corporate-information | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| parent = \n| num_employees = 86,564 (2018)\n| traded_as = {{New York Stock Exchange|DAL}}<br/>[[Dow Jones Transportation Average]] component<br/>[[S&P 500 Index]] component\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1925|3|2}}<br/>(as [[Huff Daland Dusters]])<br/>[[Macon, Georgia]], U.S.<ref name=journey/>\n| commenced = {{Start date|1929|06|17}}<ref name=NAAH>{{cite book|last1=Norwood |first1=Tom |last2=Wegg |first2=John |title=North American Airlines Handbook |publisher=Airways International |location=Sandpoint, Idaho |year=2002 |edition=3rd |isbn=0-9653993-8-9 |page=40}}</ref>\n| ceased = \n| ISIN = US2473617023\n| subsidiaries = {{Collapsible list\n|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n|title=Subsidiary List\n  |1=Aero Assurance Ltd.\n  |2=Cardinal Insurance Company (Cayman) Ltd.\n  |3=Crown Rooms, Inc.\n  |6=Delta Air Lines, Inc. and Pan American World Airways, Inc.\u2014Unterstutzungskasse GMBH\n  |7=Delta Air Lines Dublin Limited\n  |8=Delta Air Lines Private Limited\n  |9=Delta Benefits Management, Inc.\n  |10=Delta Loyalty Management Services, LLC\n  |11=[[Delta Private Jets]]<ref name=dpj>{{cite web |url=https://www.deltaprivatejets.com/about-delta-private-jets/ |title=Delta Private Jets |publisher=Delta Private Jets |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161533/https://www.deltaprivatejets.com/about-delta-private-jets/ |archive-date=July 21, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n  |12=[[Endeavor Air]]\n  |13=Epsilon Trading, LLC\n  |14=Kappa Capital Management, LLC\n  |15=Delta Vacations\n  |16=Montana Enterprises, Inc.\n  |17=New Sky, Ltd.\n  |18=Northwest Aerospace Training Corporation\n  |19=*[[Regional Elite Airline Services]], LLC\n  |20=Segrave Aviation, Inc.\n  |21=Tomisato Shoji Kabushiki Kaisha\n}}\n| headquarters = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| key_people = C.E. Woolman ([[Organizational founder|founder]])<br>[[Ed Bastian]] ([[CEO]])<br>Glen Hauenstein ([[President (corporate title)|President]])<br>Joanne Smith (E.V.P. & Chief People Officer)\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]47.007 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"Results2019\">{{cite web |title=Delta Air Lines Financials |url=https://ir.delta.com/financials/default.aspx |publisher=Delta Air Lines |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]6.618 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"Results2019\"/>\n| net_income = {{increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]4.767 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"Results2019\"/>\n| assets = {{increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]64.529 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"Results2019\"/>\n| website = {{URL|https://www.delta.com/}}\n| notes = <ref name=10K>{{cite web | url=https://www.sec.gov/ix?doc=/Archives/edgar/data/27904/000002790419000003/dal1231201810k.htm | title=DELTA AIR LINES, INC. 2018 Form 10-K Annual Report | publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Delta Air Lines, Inc.''', typically referred to as '''Delta''', is one of the [[major airlines of the United States]] and a [[legacy carrier]]. It is headquartered in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://av-info.faa.gov/detail.asp?DSGN_CODE=DALA&OPER_FAR=121&OPER_NAME=DELTA+AIR+LINES+INC| title=Federal Aviation Administration \u2013 Airline Certificate Information \u2013 Detail View| publisher=[[Federal Aviation Administration]]| access-date=September 26, 2007| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/68GHIYVXW?url=http://av-info.faa.gov/detail.asp?DSGN_CODE=DALA| archive-date=June 8, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> The airline, along with its subsidiaries and regional affiliates, including [[Delta Connection]], operates over 5,400 flights daily and serves 325 destinations in 52 countries on six continents.<ref name=\"statsfacts\">{{cite web | url=http://news.delta.com/corporate-stats-and-facts/ | title=Corporate Stats and Facts | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=August 7, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801131900/http://news.delta.com/corporate-stats-and-facts | archive-date=August 1, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> Delta is a founding member of the [[SkyTeam]] [[airline alliance]].<ref name=\"statsfacts\" />\n\nDelta has nine hubs, with [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta]] being its largest in terms of total passengers and number of departures.<ref name=\"statsfacts\" /> It is ranked second among the [[world's largest airlines]] by number of scheduled passengers carried, revenue passenger-kilometers flown, and fleet size. It is ranked 69th on the [[Fortune 500]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://fortune.com/fortune500/delta-air-lines/ | title=Fortune 500: Delta Airlines | publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014954/https://fortune.com/fortune500/delta-air-lines/ | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Delta Air Lines}}\n\n===Early history===\nDelta Air Lines' history begins with the world's first aerial [[crop dusting]] operation called [[Huff Daland Dusters, Inc.]] The company was founded on March 2, 1925, in [[Macon, Georgia]], and moved to [[Monroe, Louisiana]], in summer 1925.<ref name=\"Founding\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/founding|title=Founding|website=www.deltamuseum.org|access-date=2019-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001235928/https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/founding|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> They flew a Huff-Daland Duster, the first true crop duster, designed to combat the [[boll weevil]] infestation of cotton crops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/aircraft-by-type/crop-duster/Huff-Daland-Duster|title=Huff Daland Duster, 1925-ca.1948|last=|first=|date=|website=www.deltamuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002171508/http://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/aircraft-by-type/crop-duster/Huff-Daland-Duster|archive-date=October 2, 2019|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> [[Collett E. Woolman|C.E. Woolman]], general manager and later Delta's first CEO, led a group of local investors to acquire the company's assets. Delta Air Service was incorporated on December 3, 1928, and named after the Mississippi Delta region.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Delta: The History of an Airline|last=Lewis and Newton|first=|publisher=University of Georgia Press|year=1979|isbn=|location=Athens, Ga.|pages=20\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/leaders|title=C.E. Woolman|last=|first=|date=|website=Delta Flight Museum|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414091209/http://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/leaders|archive-date=April 14, 2019|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://news.delta.com/founder%E2%80%99s-vision-resonates-today | title=Founder's vision resonates today | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=August 19, 2015 | access-date=July 5, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705234208/https://news.delta.com/founder%E2%80%99s-vision-resonates-today | archive-date=July 5, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=journey>{{Cite web | url=https://news.delta.com/deltas-journey-timeline | title=Delta's journey: A timeline | first=Charles | last=Gay | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=April 23, 2016 | access-date=July 17, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717125757/https://news.delta.com/deltas-journey-timeline | archive-date=July 17, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPassenger operations began on June 17, 1929, from Dallas, Texas, to Jackson, Mississippi, with stops at Shreveport and Monroe, Louisiana. By June 1930, service had extended east to Atlanta and west to Fort Worth, Texas.<ref name=\"First Flights\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/first-flights|title=First Flights|website=www.deltamuseum.org|access-date=2019-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001235937/http://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/first-flights|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPassenger service ceased in October 1930 when the air mail contract for the route Delta had pioneered was awarded to another airline, which purchased the assets of Delta Air Service. Local banker Travis Oliver, acting as trustee, C.E. Woolman and other local investors purchased back the crop-dusting assets of Delta Air Service and incorporated as Delta Air Corporation on December 31, 1930.\n\nDelta Air Corporation secured an air mail contract in 1934, and began doing business as Delta Air Lines over Mail Route 24, stretching from Fort Worth, Texas, to Charleston, South Carolina.<ref name=\"First Flights\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title=Delta: The History of an Airline|last=Lewis and Newton|first=|publisher=University of Georgia Press|year=1979|isbn=|location=Athens, Ga.|pages=28\u201329, 43}}</ref><ref name=\"Founding\"/>\n\nDelta moved its headquarters from [[Monroe, Louisiana]], to its current location in [[Atlanta]] in 1941.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deltamuseum.org/docs/site/brochure/headquarters_booklet_2019edits.pdf?sfvrsn=2db8be21_2|title=Historic Aerospace Site: Delta Air Lines Headquarters, Atlanta, Georgia|last=|first=|date=|work=American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001235958/http://www.deltamuseum.org/docs/site/brochure/headquarters_booklet_2019edits.pdf?sfvrsn=2db8be21_2|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The company name officially became Delta Air Lines in 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/timeline/decades/1940|title=1940s|website=www.deltamuseum.org|access-date=2019-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001235925/https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/timeline/decades/1940|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1946, the company commenced regularly scheduled [[freight transport]]. In 1949, the company launched the first discounted fares between [[Chicago]] and [[Miami]]. In 1953, the company launched its first international routes after the acquisition of [[Chicago and Southern Air Lines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/family-tree/chicago-southern-air-lines|title=Chicago & Southern Air Lines|website=www.deltamuseum.org|access-date=2019-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428062154/http://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/family-tree/chicago-southern-air-lines|archive-date=April 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1959, it was the first airline to fly the [[Douglas DC-8]]. In 1960, it was the first airline to fly [[Convair 880]] jets. In 1964, it launched the Deltamatic reservation systems using computers in the [[IBM 7070]] series. In 1965, Delta was the first airline to fly the [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]].\n\n===Growth and acquisitions===\nBy 1970, Delta had an all-jet fleet, and in 1972 it acquired [[Northeast Airlines]]. Trans-Atlantic service began in 1978 with the first nonstop flights from Atlanta to [[London]]. In 1981, Delta launched a [[frequent-flyer program]]. In 1987, it acquired [[Western Airlines]], and that same year Delta began trans-Pacific service (Atlanta-Portland, Oregon-Tokyo). In 1990, Delta was the first airline in the United States to fly [[McDonnell Douglas MD-11]] jets. In 1991, it acquired substantially all of [[Pan American World Airways|Pan Am]]'s trans-Atlantic routes and the Pan Am Shuttle, rebranded as the [[Delta Shuttle]]. Delta was now the leading airline across the Atlantic.<ref name=\"journey\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/timeline/decades/1920|title=Delta Timeline|last=Delta Flight Museum|first=|date=|website=www.deltamuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414091215/http://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/timeline/decades/1920|archive-date=April 14, 2019|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Delta was the first airline to board more than 100 million passengers in a calendar year. Also that year, Delta began an expansion of their international routes into [[Latin America]].<ref>{{cite web | title=1990s-Delta History | url=https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/timeline/decades/1990 | publisher=[[Delta Flight Museum]] | access-date=May 13, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513215208/https://www.deltamuseum.org/exhibits/delta-history/timeline/decades/1990 | archive-date=May 13, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the company launched [[Song (airline)|Song]], a [[low-cost carrier]].<ref name=journey/>\n\n===Bankruptcy and restructuring (2005-2007)===\nOn September 14, 2005, the company filed for [[bankruptcy]], citing rising fuel costs.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2005/09/12/daily17.html | title=Delta files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy | first=Rachel Tobin | last=Ramos | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=September 14, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2005/09/14/news/fortune500/delta/ | title=Delta Air Lines files for bankruptcy | first=Chris | last=Isidore | work=[[CNN]] | date=September 15, 2005 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161533/https://money.cnn.com/2005/09/14/news/fortune500/delta/ | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/delta-files-for-bankruptcy/ | title=Delta Files For Bankruptcy | first=Gina | last=Pace | work=[[CBS News]] | date=September 14, 2005 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161532/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/delta-files-for-bankruptcy/ | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> It emerged from bankruptcy in April 2007 after fending off a [[hostile takeover]] from [[US Airways]] and its shares were re-listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-delta-bankruptcy/delta-exits-bankruptcy-after-19-month-restructuring-idUSWNAS850820070430 | title=Delta exits bankruptcy after 19-month restructuring | first=Chris | last=Reiter | work=[[Reuters]] | date=April 30, 2007 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161534/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-delta-bankruptcy/delta-exits-bankruptcy-after-19-month-restructuring-idUSWNAS850820070430 | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/delta-air-lines-emerges-from-bankruptcy | title=Delta Air Lines exits bankruptcy | first1=Aude | last1=Lagorce | first2=Padraic | last2=Cassidy | work=[[Marketwatch]] | date=April 30, 2007 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161530/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/delta-air-lines-emerges-from-bankruptcy | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2007/04/30/news/companies/delta_bankruptcy/index.htm | title=Delta exits bankruptcy with planes full | first=Chris | last=Isidore | work=[[CNN]] | date=April 30, 2007 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161530/https://money.cnn.com/2007/04/30/news/companies/delta_bankruptcy/index.htm | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Acquisition of Northwest Airlines (2008)===\nThe acquisition of [[Northwest Airlines]] was announced April 14, 2008. It was approved and consummated on October 29, 2008. Northwest continued to operate as a wholly owned subsidiary of Delta until December 31, 2009, when the Northwest Airlines operating certificate was merged into that of Delta.<ref>{{cite news | title=Delta, Northwest approved to fly under single operating certificate | url=https://travel.usatoday.com/flights/post/2009/12/delta-northwest-approved-to-fly-under-single-operating-certificate/13205/1 | first=Rebecca | last=Heslin | work=[[USA Today]] | date=December 31, 2009 | access-date=April 30, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413073916/http://travel.usatoday.com/flights/post/2009/12/delta-northwest-approved-to-fly-under-single-operating-certificate/13205/1 | archive-date=April 13, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> Delta completed integration with Northwest on January 31, 2010, when their [[computer reservations system]] and websites were combined, and the Northwest Airlines brand was officially retired.<ref name=\"mouawad\">{{cite news | title=Delta-Northwest Merger's Long and Complex Path | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/19/business/19air.html | author=Jad Mouawad | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 18, 2011 | url-access=subscription | access-date=February 7, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331010155/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/19/business/19air.html | archive-date=March 31, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Destinations and hubs==\n===Destinations===\n{{main|List of Delta Air Lines destinations|List of Delta Connection destinations}}\n\nDelta and its worldwide alliance partners operate more than 15,000 flights per day.<ref name=\"statsfacts\"/>\n\nDelta is the only U.S. carrier that flies to [[Kotoka International Airport|Accra]], [[Copenhagen Airport|Copenhagen]], [[Blaise Diagne International Airport|Dakar]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf Airport|D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[OR Tambo International Airport|Johannesburg]], [[Murtala Muhammed International Airport|Lagos]], [[Nice Cote d'Azur Airport|Nice]], and [[Stuttgart Airport|Stuttgart]].\n\nIn March 2020, Delta announced they are suspending all flights to continental Europe for 30 days, and cutting 40% of their capacity.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-air-lines-cutting-40-of-capacity-11584119024?mod=business_lead_pos3</ref>\n\n===Hubs===\nDelta currently has nine hubs.<ref name=statsfacts /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/airlines-airports/delta/delta-hubs-around-the-world | title=Where Travelers Can Find Delta Air Lines Hubs | first=MOLLY | last=MCARDLE | work=[[Travel + Leisure]] | date=February 23, 2018 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014953/https://www.travelandleisure.com/airlines-airports/delta/delta-hubs-around-the-world | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta]] \u2013 Delta's hub for the Southeast and its main gateway to Latin America and the Caribbean. In addition to its corporate headquarters, Delta operates its primary hub in Atlanta as well as [[Delta TechOps]], which is Delta's primary maintenance base.<ref name=\"ATLlargestHub\">{{cite news | last=Yamanouchi | first=Kelly | title=Delta says Atlanta hub is world\u2019s most profitable, poised for growth | url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/airport/delta-says-atlanta-hub-world-most-profitable-poised-for-growth/xUR4xD5UzE7aA3hVrTkyKK/ | work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] | date=December 17, 2015 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161530/https://www.ajc.com/blog/airport/delta-says-atlanta-hub-world-most-profitable-poised-for-growth/xUR4xD5UzE7aA3hVrTkyKK/ | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Logan International Airport|Boston]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-upgrades-boston-to-hub-status-on-strong-growth-458669/|title=Delta upgrades Boston to hub status on strong growth|last=Russell|first=Edward|date=2019-06-03|website=Flightglobal.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807030740/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-upgrades-boston-to-hub-status-on-strong-growth-458669/|archive-date=August 7, 2019|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> \u2013 Delta's secondary transatlantic hub. Boston-Logan had previously been a Delta hub from the latter half of the 20th century to the early 2000s. The present Terminal A was built for Delta's sole use, but following the 2005 bankruptcy, Delta scaled back operations and leased 11 gates in the terminal. Delta subsequently regained all the Terminal A gates and began building up operations again in the mid 2010s, culminating in the reestablishing of BOS as a hub in 2019.\n*[[Detroit Metropolitan Airport|Detroit]] \u2013 Inherited through the [[Delta Air Lines-Northwest Airlines merger|merger with Northwest]], Detroit serves as one of Delta's two Midwest hubs and is Delta's second largest overall. It is the primary Asian gateway for the Eastern United States and it also provides service to many destinations in the Americas and Europe.\n*[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]] \u2013 Delta's secondary West Coast hub. Delta inherited its LAX hub from [[Western Airlines]], but dismantled it in the mid-1990s, opting to relocate most of those aircraft to the east coast. Since then, it has re-opened the hub, offering service to select cities in Latin America, Asia, Australia and Europe, as well as major domestic cities and West Coast regional destinations.\n*[[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]] \u2013 Inherited through the [[Delta Air Lines-Northwest Airlines merger|merger with Northwest]], Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul serves as one of Delta's two Midwest hubs and is Delta's third largest overall. It is the primary Canadian gateway for the airline while also including many American metropolitan destinations, a number of regional destinations in the upper Midwest as well as some select destinations in Europe and Asia.\n* [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York\u2013JFK]] \u2013  Delta's primary transatlantic hub. Delta inherited its JFK hub from its partnership with Pan Am after Pan Am's collapse in 1991. The hub also offers service on many transcontinental \"prestige routes\" to west coast destinations such as Los Angeles and San Francisco.\n*[[LaGuardia Airport|New York\u2013LaGuardia]] \u2013 Delta's second New York hub. This important domestic hub was created as a result of a slot swap with the now defunct [[US Airways]]. Delta's service at LaGuardia covers numerous East Coast US cities, and a number of regional destinations in the US and Canada.\n*[[Salt Lake City International Airport|Salt Lake City]] \u2013 Inherited through the [[Western Airlines|merger with Western Airlines]], Salt Lake City serves as the fourth largest hub for the airline. Delta service covers most major US destinations as well as a number of regional destinations in the US, with an emphasis on the Rocky Mountain region, as well as select destinations in Canada, Mexico, and select cities in Europe and Hawaii.\n*[[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]] \u2013 Delta's primary West Coast hub. The hub serves as an international gateway to Asia for the Western United States. Delta service also includes many major US destinations as well as regional destinations in the Pacific Northwest. Delta started aggressively building its presence in Seattle in 2011, and announced SEA's hub status in 2014, while notably sparking tensions with Seattle-based Alaska Airlines.<ref name=\"airchive.com\">{{cite web |url=http://airchive.com/blog/2014/06/17/delta-launches-seattle-hong-kong/ |title=Delta Launches Seattle-Hong Kong, and Seattle Hub - June 17, 2014 |publisher=airchive.com |accessdate=June 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140621061046/http://airchive.com/blog/2014/06/17/delta-launches-seattle-hong-kong/ |archive-date=June 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Alliance and codeshare agreements===\nDelta was a founding member of the [[SkyTeam]] Alliance in 2000,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.skyteam.com/en/about/history/2000/ | title=2000 | publisher=[[SkyTeam]] | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015229/https://www.skyteam.com/en/about/history/2000 | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and has [[codeshare agreement]]s with the following airlines:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/where-we-fly/flight-partners.html | title=FLIGHT PARTNERS | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822150828/https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/where-we-fly/flight-partners.html | archive-date=August 22, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/delta-air-lines-dl |title=Profile on Delta Air Lines | website=CAPA | publisher=Centre for Aviation|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030164915/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/delta-air-lines-dl |archive-date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* [[Aeroflot]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Delta resumes Aeroflot domestic Russia codeshares from Sep 2017 |url=http://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/274871/delta-resumes-aeroflot-domestic-russia-codeshares-from-sep-2017/ |accessdate=September 20, 2017 |work=Routesonline |date=September 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920192348/http://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/274871/delta-resumes-aeroflot-domestic-russia-codeshares-from-sep-2017/ |archive-date=September 20, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-aerol-neas-argentinas-partnership-launches | title=Delta, Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas partnership launches | first=Sarah | last=Lora | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=November 30, 2015 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161807/https://news.delta.com/delta-aerol-neas-argentinas-partnership-launches | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Aerom\u00e9xico]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://pro.delta.com/content/agency/us/en/agent-resources/partner-information/delta---aeromexico-joint-cooperation-agreement.html | title=Delta - Aeromexico Joint Cooperation Agreement | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014953/https://pro.delta.com/content/agency/us/en/agent-resources/partner-information/delta---aeromexico-joint-cooperation-agreement.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Air Europa]] \n* [[Air France]]\n* [[Alitalia]] \n* [[China Airlines]] \n* [[China Eastern Airlines]] \n* [[China Southern Airlines]]\n* [[Czech Airlines]] \n* [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n* [[Gol Transportes A\u00e9reos]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/expanded-delta-gol-codeshare-connects-florida-brasilia-and-fortaleza | title=Expanded Delta-GOL codeshare connects Florida to Brasilia and Fortaleza | first=Sarah | last=Lora | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=June 19, 2018 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015001/https://news.delta.com/expanded-delta-gol-codeshare-connects-florida-brasilia-and-fortaleza | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Hawaiian Airlines]]\n* [[Kenya Airways]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-and-kenya-airways-expand-connectivity-between-us-and-africa | title=Delta Air Lines and Kenya Airways expand connectivity between U.S. and Africa | first=Olivia | last=Cullis | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=August 15, 2018 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161531/https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-and-kenya-airways-expand-connectivity-between-us-and-africa | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[KLM]]\n* [[Korean Air]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-and-korean-air-enhance-codeshare-flights-us | title=Delta and Korean Air enhance codeshare flights in the U.S. | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=June 1, 2018 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015004/https://news.delta.com/delta-and-korean-air-enhance-codeshare-flights-us | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Seaborne Airlines]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-seaborne-codeshare-expands-travel-options-us-caribbean | title=Delta & Seaborne codeshare expands travel options to U.S., Caribbean | first=Sarah | last=Lora | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=July 18, 2016 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015225/https://news.delta.com/delta-seaborne-codeshare-expands-travel-options-us-caribbean | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Transavia]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-agreement-transavia-opens-new-destinations | title=Delta agreement with Transavia opens new destinations | first=Debbie | last=Egerton | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=March 2, 2016 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015548/https://news.delta.com/delta-agreement-transavia-opens-new-destinations | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Vietnam Airlines]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-welcomes-vietnam-airlines-skyteam-alliance | title=Delta Welcomes Vietnam Airlines into SkyTeam Alliance | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=June 10, 2010 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015129/https://news.delta.com/delta-welcomes-vietnam-airlines-skyteam-alliance | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Virgin Atlantic]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/where-we-fly/flight-partners/virgin-atlantic-partnership/virgin-atlantic-faqs.html | title=VIRGIN ATLANTIC PARTNERSHIP FAQS | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014953/https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/where-we-fly/flight-partners/virgin-atlantic-partnership/virgin-atlantic-faqs.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Virgin Australia]]\n* [[WestJet]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-and-westjet-create-new-transborder-joint-venture | title=Delta and WestJet to create new transborder joint venture | first=Debbie | last=Egerton | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=July 18, 2018 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015007/https://news.delta.com/delta-and-westjet-create-new-transborder-joint-venture | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Joint ventures===\nIn addition to the above codeshares, Delta has also entered into joint ventures with the following airlines.\n\n*[[Aeromexico]] \u2013 Delta owns 49% of Mexican [[flag carrier]] Aerom\u00e9xico. In 2015, Delta and Aeromexico applied for an immunized joint venture. After two years, the joint venture was approved with two conditions: both airlines had to surrender four slot pairs at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] and 24 at [[Mexico City International Airport]] to competitors (both airports have slot restrictions). The joint venture began in May 2017, at which time Aeromexico moved to Delta gates at both Kennedy and [[Los Angeles International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/aeromexico-and-delta-launch-long-sought-joint-ventur-436903/ | title=Aeromexico and Delta launch long-sought joint venture | last=Russell | first=Edward | work=[[Flightglobal]] | date=9 May 2017 | access-date=June 17, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229184918/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/aeromexico-and-delta-launch-long-sought-joint-ventur-436903/ | archive-date=December 29, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Air France]]/[[KLM]]/[[Alitalia]] \u2013 Delta, as successor to Northwest Airlines, has a transatlantic joint venture with [[Air France\u2013KLM]] and Alitalia. The program coordinates trans-Atlantic operations, including ticket pricing, schedules, capacity, and revenue. On January 27, 2012, the [[European Commission]] launched an investigation into possible violations of [[competition law]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dw.com/en/eu-launches-antitrust-probe-into-skyteam-airline-alliance/a-15699162 | title=EU launches antitrust probe into SkyTeam airline alliance | work=[[Deutsche Welle]] | date=January 27, 2012 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161536/https://www.dw.com/en/eu-launches-antitrust-probe-into-skyteam-airline-alliance/a-15699162 | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Korean Air]] \u2013 In 2016, Delta and Korean Air began to lay the groundwork for a trans-Pacific joint venture to compete against those between [[American Airlines]] and [[Japan Airlines]], and [[United Airlines]] and [[All Nippon Airways]]. Unlike other planned joint ventures, the Delta-Korean Air joint venture was quick to receive approval by both the US Department of Transportation and the Korean Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stattimes.com/delta-korean-air-to-jointly-increase-belly-cargo-alliance-across-transpacific-air-cargo|title=Delta, Korean Air to jointly increase belly cargo alliance across trans-Pacific {{!}} Air Cargo|last=TIMES|first=The STAT TRADE|website=www.stattimes.com|access-date=2018-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403173523/https://www.stattimes.com/delta-korean-air-to-jointly-increase-belly-cargo-alliance-across-transpacific-air-cargo|archive-date=April 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> They aim to increase belly cargo cooperation and offer benefits to its customers across one of the most comprehensive route networks in the trans-Pacific market. This joint venture gives Delta and Korean Air's shared customers seamless access to more than 290 destinations in the Americas and more than 80 in Asia. This joint venture officially launched in May 2018, exactly one year after the joint venture with Aeromexico began.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avitrader.com/2018/03/29/delta-and-korean-air-to-launch-joint-venture-partnership/|title=Delta and Korean Air to launch joint venture partnership|date=2018-03-29|work=AviTrader Aviation News|access-date=2018-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403234636/https://www.avitrader.com/2018/03/29/delta-and-korean-air-to-launch-joint-venture-partnership/|archive-date=April 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[LATAM Airlines Group]] - In September 2019, Delta announced its plans to buy 20% of LATAM Airlines Group for $1.9 billion which will expand Delta's access to Latin America. In related transactions, Delta is paying to withdraw LATAM from [[oneworld]] and also acquired the undelivered [[Airbus A350 XWB]] aircraft from the LATAM order book along with two aircraft leased externally by LATAM.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/latam-airlines-ma-delta-air/delta-to-buy-20-of-latam-for-1-9-billion-in-regional-shake-up-idUSL2N26H1U3 |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926225532/https://www.reuters.com/article/latam-airlines-ma-delta-air/delta-to-buy-20-of-latam-for-1-9-billion-in-regional-shake-up-idUSL2N26H1U3 |archive-date=September 26, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The acquisition of the stake was completed on December 30, 2019.<ref>{{citenews | url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/airlines/delta-completes-purchase-of-20-percent-stake-in-latam.html |title=Delta Completes Purchase of 20 Percent Stake in LATAM | last=Christoff | first=Janeen | work=[[TravelPulse]] | date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Virgin Atlantic]] \u2013 On December 11, 2012, Delta announced that it would acquire the 49% stake in Virgin Atlantic held by [[Singapore Airlines]] for $360 million. The two airlines operate a total of 31 roundtrip flights between the UK and North America, including nine daily roundtrip flights between [[London Heathrow|London]] and New York City airports (John F. Kennedy International Airport and [[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark]]), with costs shared between the two airlines.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-and-virgin-atlantic-form-strategic-alliance | title=Delta and Virgin Atlantic To Form Strategic Alliance | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=December 11, 2012 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161627/https://news.delta.com/delta-and-virgin-atlantic-form-strategic-alliance | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The two airlines' application for antitrust immunity was granted by the [[United States Department of Transportation]] on September 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-and-virgin-atlantic-airways-welcome-us-department-transportation-decision-grant | title=Delta Air Lines and Virgin Atlantic Airways Welcome U.S. Department of Transportation decision to grant Antitrust Immunity | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=September 23, 2013 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015246/https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-and-virgin-atlantic-airways-welcome-us-department-transportation-decision-grant | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Virgin Australia]] \u2013 In 2017, Delta announced a joint venture with Virgin Australia, strengthening its trans-Pacific network and allowing the carrier to add direct flights between Australia and the United States.\n* [[WestJet]] \u2013 Delta Air Lines and Canadian airline WestJet operate a codeshare agreement on select routes in North America. On July 19, 2018, WestJet and Delta Air Lines signed a ten-year agreement. The airlines' also aligned their frequent flier programs and are co-located at key hub airports.\n\n==Fleet==\n<!--\n\nPlease do not add a fleet table to this section. Detailed fleet information is covered in the posted Delta Air Lines fleet article.\n\n-->\n[[File:N647DL-2008-08-15-YVR.jpg|thumb|Delta Air Lines has the largest Boeing 757 fleet of any airline.]]\n[[File:Delta Airlines - Boeing 767-300 - N185DN (Quintin Soloviev).jpg|thumb|A Delta Air Lines [[Boeing 767]]-300ER at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]]]]\n{{Main|Delta Air Lines fleet}}\n\n{{As of|2020|3|}}, Delta operates a fleet of 913 aircraft<ref name=\"Planespotters-Delta\" /> manufactured by [[Airbus]], [[Boeing Commercial Airplanes|Boeing]], and [[McDonnell Douglas]].<ref name=\"statsfacts\" /> Delta operates the largest [[Boeing 717]], [[Boeing 757]], [[Boeing 767]], [[McDonnell Douglas MD-88]], and [[McDonnell Douglas MD-90]] fleets in the world, and the largest [[Airbus A330]] fleet of any US airline. Prior to its 2008 merger with Northwest Airlines, Delta's fleet was made up of solely Boeing and McDonnell Douglas aircraft. Airbus aircraft from Northwest joined the fleet after the merger, and more have since been added.\n\nDelta often seeks to acquire and utilize older aircraft, especially narrow-bodies, and it has created an extensive MRO (maintenance, repair, and overhaul) organization, called TechOps, to support them. The oldest aircraft in the fleet are the McDonnell Douglas MD-88s, with an average age of over 25 years.<ref name=\"fleetsize\">{{cite web |url=http://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/about-delta/corporate-information/aircraft-fleet.html |title=Corporate Information: Aircraft Fleet & Investor Relations |publisher=Delta Air Lines |access-date=June 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418032509/http://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/about-delta/corporate-information/aircraft-fleet.html |archive-date=April 18, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, in early 2011, Delta began talks with Airbus, Boeing and [[Bombardier Aerospace]] to discuss replacing the McDonnell Douglas DC-9s, MD-88s, and older [[Airbus A320 family|A320]] and [[757-200]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/12/17/351072/delta-prepares-for-full-narrowbody-analysis-in-early.html |title=Delta prepares for full narrowbody analysis in early 2011 |first=Lori |last=Ranson |date=December 17, 2011 |work=Flight International |publisher=Reed Business Information |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220043430/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/12/17/351072/delta-prepares-for-full-narrowbody-analysis-in-early.html |archivedate=December 20, 2010 |accessdate=January 15, 2011 |quote=...Delta president Ed Bastian said: \"We clearly need to get the DC-9s retired. We clearly need to start to build a replenishment strategy for our older MD-88s and some of our Airbus narrow bodies as well as the [Boeing] 757-200s. |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> On August 22, 2011, Delta placed an order for 100 [[Boeing 737-900ER]] aircraft<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2011/08/22/361106/delta-to-cap-its-narrowbody-order-at-100-737-900ers.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105184838/http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-to-cap-its-narrowbody-order-at-100-737-900ers-361106/ |archivedate=November 5, 2012 |title=Delta to cap its narrowbody order at 100 737-900ERs |date= August 22, 2011 |work=Flightglobal |publisher=Air Transport Intelligence news |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> and deferred an order of 100 small narrow-body jets until 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-08-24/delta-air-said-to-defer-order-of-100-small-single-aisle-jets-until-2012 | title=Delta Said to Defer Order of 100 Small Narrow-Body Jets to 2012 | first1=Mary Jane | last1=Credeur | first2=Jose Sergio | last2=Osse | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=August 25, 2011 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161851/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-08-24/delta-air-said-to-defer-order-of-100-small-single-aisle-jets-until-2012 | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs part of its strategy to operate less-expensive used airplanes, Delta agreed in 2012 to lease 88 Boeing 717s acquired by [[Southwest Airlines]] as part of its acquisition of [[AirTran Airways]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Schlangenstein | first=Mary | title=Delta Mixes Old, New Jets in CEO's Cost-Cutting Fleet Plan | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-30/delta-mixes-old-jets-with-new-in-ceo-s-cost-cutting-fleet-plan | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=September 30, 2013 | access-date=March 6, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017201435/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-30/delta-mixes-old-jets-with-new-in-ceo-s-cost-cutting-fleet-plan | archive-date=October 17, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> They replaced some DC-9s and some 50-seat regional aircraft such as the [[CRJ-200]]. The first revenue flight was on October 25, 2013,<ref>{{cite news | title=Now Flying For Delta: The Boeing 717 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2013/10/25/delta-launches-first-boeing-717-flights/3189607/ | first=Ben | last=Mutzabaugh | work=[[USA Today]] | date=October 25, 2013 | access-date=August 27, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710193412/https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2013/10/25/delta-launches-first-boeing-717-flights/3189607/ | archive-date=July 10, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Delta officially retired its last DC-9 on January 6, 2014; it was used on an as-needed basis until January 22, 2014, when the last one was removed from service.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://airwaysmag.com/airlines/dc-9-completes-final-scheduled-flight/ | title=End of an Era: Delta's DC-9 Completes Final Scheduled Flight | work=[[Airways (magazine)|Airways]] | date=January 6, 2014 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161533/https://airwaysmag.com/airlines/dc-9-completes-final-scheduled-flight/ | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Delta was the final US carrier operating the DC-9.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/dc9-retirement/index.html | title=Last days of the DC-9: The jet that connected America | first=Thom | last=Patterson | work=[[CNN]] | date=January 11, 2014 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161530/https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/dc9-retirement/index.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> As a continuation of the narrowbody fleet refresh and expansion, Delta ordered 75, and later expanded that order to 95, [[Airbus A220]] (formerly the Bombardier CSeries) aircraft, and became the first American carrier to order the plane.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bombardier-delta-1.3556661 | title=Delta buying 75 Bombardier CSeries jets, with options for 50 more | first=Pete | last=Evans | work=[[CBC News]] | date=April 28, 2016 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828095520/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/bombardier-delta-1.3556661 | archive-date=August 28, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.bombardier.com/en/media/newsList/details.delta-air-lines-and-bombardier-sign-largest-c-series-order-for-u0.bombardiercom.html | title=Delta Air Lines and Bombardier Sign Largest C Series order for up to 125 Aircraft | publisher=[[Bombardier Inc.|Bombardier]] | date=April 28, 2016 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161533/https://www.bombardier.com/en/media/newsList/details.delta-air-lines-and-bombardier-sign-largest-c-series-order-for-u0.bombardiercom.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delta.com/delta-expands-a220-order-book-5-aircraft-95-total-techops-signs-mou-a220-flight-hour-services|title=Delta expands A220 order book by 5 aircraft to 95 total; TechOps signs MOU for A220 Flight Hour Services|website=Delta News Hub|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815151246/https://news.delta.com/delta-expands-a220-order-book-5-aircraft-95-total-techops-signs-mou-a220-flight-hour-services|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe airline has not been as keen to acquire or operate aging wide-body aircraft. In August 2014, Delta announced it would begin to retire its aging [[Boeing 747-400]] fleet, which Delta acquired as part of the Northwest merger.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/delta-to-let-four-747s-fl_b_5639890 | title=Delta to Let Four 747s Fly Out of the Fleet | first=Christine | last=Negroni | work=[[HuffPost]] | date=August 1, 2014 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805084505/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/delta-to-let-four-747s-fl_b_5639890 | archive-date=August 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> During a 2014 earnings call, CEO [[Richard H. Anderson (businessman)|Richard Anderson]] announced that they would be retired by the end of 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2014/10/16/delta-ceo-boeing-747s-will-be-retired-by-2017/17350781/ | title=Delta CEO: Boeing 747s will be retired by 2017 | work=[[USA Today]] | date=October 16, 2014 | access-date=August 27, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823093232/https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2014/10/16/delta-ceo-boeing-747s-will-be-retired-by-2017/17350781/ | archive-date=August 23, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> On November 20, 2014, the airline announced an order for 25 [[Airbus A350 XWB]] and 25 [[Airbus A330neo]] aircraft to replace the 747 fleet as it was retired, as well as some aging 767s. A350 deliveries began in the second quarter of 2017, while the first A330-900neo flew in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delta.com/delta-launches-a330-900neo-service-bringing-premium-products-and-service-more-customers-seattle-and|title=Delta launches A330-900neo service, bringing premium products and service to more customers in Seattle and beyond|website=Delta News Hub|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815151235/https://news.delta.com/delta-launches-a330-900neo-service-bringing-premium-products-and-service-more-customers-seattle-and|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Delta retired the 747 on January 3, 2018, with its final revenue flight from Seoul-Incheon to Detroit (DL158) occurring on December 19, 2017, becoming the last major U.S. airline to fly the 747.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2018/01/04/delta-air-lines-sends-its-last-boeing-747-arizona-boneyard/1002717001/ | title=Delta Air Lines sends its last Boeing 747 to Arizona 'boneyard' | first=Ben | last=Mutzabaugh | work=[[USA Today]] | date=January 4, 2018 | access-date=January 23, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124072645/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2018/01/04/delta-air-lines-sends-its-last-boeing-747-arizona-boneyard/1002717001/ | archive-date=January 24, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/final-747-flight-now-scheduled-monday | title=Final 747 flight now scheduled for Monday | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=December 17, 2017 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801021425/https://news.delta.com/final-747-flight-now-scheduled-monday | archive-date=August 1, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 14, 2017, Delta ordered 100 [[Airbus A321neo]]s, with 100 further options for $25.4 billion at list prices, to be delivered from 2020; equipped with [[Pratt & Whitney]] [[PW1100G]]s and configured with a maximum capacity of 197 passengers, they will replace the airline's aging [[Airbus A319]]s, Airbus A320s, Boeing 757-200s, MD-88s and MD-90s.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-picks-a321neo-for-narrowbody-replacement-444153/ |title= Delta picks A321neo for narrowbody replacement |date= December 14, 2017 |author= Edward Russell |work= Flightglobal |access-date= December 14, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171214143445/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-picks-a321neo-for-narrowbody-replacement-444153/ |archive-date= December 14, 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Cabin==\n\nDelta underwent a cabin branding upgrade in 2015.<ref name=\"CabinRefresh\">{{cite news | title=Delta offers redefined cabin, premium amenity options | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-offers-redefined-cabin-premium-amenity-options | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=December 8, 2014 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021201758/https://news.delta.com/delta-offers-redefined-cabin-premium-amenity-options | archive-date=October 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The airline now offers or plans to offer six different cabin service options: Delta One, Delta Premium Select, First Class, Comfort+, Main Cabin, and Basic Economy. Availability and exact details vary by route and aircraft type.\n\n===Delta One===\n[[File:Delta One Suites (41341308490).jpg|thumb|Delta One Suite on a Boeing 777]]\n\nDelta One is the airline's premier [[business class]] product, available on long haul international flights, as well as [[Transcontinental flight|transcontinental]] service from [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]] to [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], [[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]] and [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]].<ref name=\"CabinRefresh\"/>\n\nDelta One features lie-flat seating on all aircraft types, and direct aisle access from every seat on all types except the Boeing 757-200 (in which only a special sub-fleet of approximately 20 aircraft feature lie-flats).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.delta.com/us/en/aircraft/boeing/757-200|title=Boeing 757-200 Aircraft Seat Maps, Specs & Amenities : Delta Air Lines|website=www.delta.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402175107/https://www.delta.com/us/en/aircraft/boeing/757-200|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Boeing 767-300ER]] and [[Boeing 767-400ER]] seats, designed by [[James Thompson (researcher)|James Thompson]], feature a space-saving design whereby the seats are staggered such that when in the fully flat position, the foot of each bed extends under the armrests of the seat in front of it. Delta One cabins on the [[Boeing 777-200ER]]/[[Boeing 777-200LR|LR]] fleet are configured in a [[herringbone seating|herringbone]] layout, while Airbus A330 cabins (featuring the ''Cirrus'' flat-bed sleeper suite by [[Zodiac Seats U.S.]]) are configured in a reverse herringbone pattern.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://multivu.prnewswire.com/mnr/delta/45973/ |title=Delta Revitalizing Boeing 747-400 Fleet with New Interiors |publisher=Multivu.prnewswire.com |date=September 2, 2010 |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110425165206/http://multivu.prnewswire.com/mnr/delta/45973/ |archive-date=April 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAll seats are also equipped with a personal, on demand in-flight-entertainment (IFE) system, universal power-ports, a movable reading light, and a folding work table. Passengers also receive complimentary chef-curated meals, refreshments, alcoholic beverages, a [[Tumi Inc.]] amenity kit, premium bedding, and pre-flight Sky Club access.<ref name=\"CabinDetails\">{{cite web | title=Customer Experience Fact Sheet | url=https://news.delta.com/customer-experience-fact-sheet | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=October 6, 2017 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015057/https://news.delta.com/customer-experience-fact-sheet | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Delta announced the introduction of Delta One Suites on select widebody fleets. The suites will feature a door to the aisle for enhanced privacy, as well as improved storage space, a larger IFE screen, and updated design. The suites will roll out on the [[Airbus A350 XWB|Airbus A350]] fleet, first delivered in July 2017, followed by installation within the Boeing 777 fleet.<ref>{{cite news | last=Savadelis | first=Liz | title=World's first all-suite business class introduced in Delta One | url=https://news.delta.com/worlds-first-all-suite-business-class-introduced-delta-one | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=August 16, 2016 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721015506/https://news.delta.com/worlds-first-all-suite-business-class-introduced-delta-one | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Thomas | first=Michael | title=Delta takes delivery of first flagship Airbus A350-900 | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-takes-delivery-first-flagship-airbus-a350-900 | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=July 13, 2017 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801023855/https://news.delta.com/delta-takes-delivery-first-flagship-airbus-a350-900 | archive-date=August 1, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Premium Select===\n[[File:A350- Interior - Premium Select (37095459120).jpg|thumb|Delta Premium Select on an Airbus A350-900]]\nIn April 2016, Delta CEO Ed Bastian announced that a new Premium Economy cabin will be added. Since renamed to Premium Select, this cabin will feature extra legroom; adjustable leg rests; extra seat pitch, width, and recline; and a new premium service. Delta introduced it on its new [[Airbus A350]], first delivered in fall 2017, to be followed by the [[Boeing 777]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Savadelis | first=Liz | title=Delta Premium Select to debut in 2017 | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-premium-select-debut-2017 | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=November 3, 2016 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729172838/https://news.delta.com/delta-premium-select-debut-2017 | archive-date=July 29, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2018, Delta announced that they would be selling First Class seats on domestically configured Boeing 757 aircraft flying transatlantic routes as '''Premium Select'''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://runwaygirlnetwork.com/2017/11/22/delta-starts-selling-757-recliners-as-international-premium-economy/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204195156/https://runwaygirlnetwork.com/2017/11/22/delta-starts-selling-757-recliners-as-international-premium-economy/ |archive-date=December 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===First Class===\n[[File:A220 First Class (44703804685).jpg|thumb|First class on a Delta A220-100]]\nFirst Class is offered on mainline domestic flights (except those featuring Delta One service), select short- and medium-haul international flights, and Delta Connection aircraft with more than 50 seats. Seats range from {{convert|18.5|to|20.75|in|cm}} wide and have between {{convert|37|and|40|in|cm}} of pitch. Passengers in this class receive a wider variety of free snacks compared to Main Cabin, as well as free drinks and alcohol, and full meal service on flights {{convert|900|mi}} and longer. Certain aircraft also feature power ports at each seat and free entertainment products from Delta Studio. First Class passengers are also eligible for priority boarding.<ref name=\"CabinDetails\"/>\n\n===Delta Comfort+===\n[[File:Interior of Delta Air Lines Airbus A321.jpg|thumb|Delta Comfort+ on an Airbus A321]]\nDelta Comfort+ seats are installed on all aircraft excluding Delta's new A350s and feature {{convert|34-36|in|mm}} of pitch; on all Delta One configured aircraft, {{convert|35-36|in|mm}} of pitch and 50 percent more recline over standard Main Cabin seats.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/onboard-experience/delta-comfort-plus.html | title=It's Simple, Plus Means More | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728032634/https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/onboard-experience/delta-comfort-plus.html | archive-date=July 28, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Additional amenities include: Sky Priority Boarding, dedicated overhead space, complimentary beer, wine, and spirits on flights {{convert|250|mi}} or more, and complimentary premium snacks on flights {{convert|900|mi}} or more. Complimentary premium entertainment is available via Delta Studio, with free headsets available on most flights.<ref name=\"CabinDetails\"/> On transcontinental flights between JFK-LAX/SFO, Delta Comfort+ passengers also get [[Luvo Inc.|Luvo]] snack wraps. Medallion members can upgrade from Main Cabin to Comfort+ for free, while other customers can upgrade for a fee or with SkyMiles.<ref>{{cite web | title=DELTA COMFORT+ FAQS | url=https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/support/faqs/booking-your-trip/delta-comfort-plus-faqs.html | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161534/https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/support/faqs/booking-your-trip/delta-comfort-plus-faqs.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Main Cabin===\n[[File:A350- Interior - Main Cabin (23645006548).jpg|thumb|Main Cabin on an Airbus A350-900]]\nMain Cabin (Economy Class) is available on all aircraft with seats ranging from {{convert|17|to|18|in|cm}} wide and {{convert|30|to|33|in|cm}} of pitch. The main cabin on Boeing 737, 777, and selected Boeing 757-200, 767-300, and McDonnell Douglas MD-90 aircraft have an articulating seat bottom where the seat bottom moves forward in addition to the seat back tilting backwards when reclining.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}<!--Everything sourced to Flyertalk can't be used--><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=43&item=870 |title=Delta to Invest in Customer Experience, Fleet Efficiency |publisher=News.delta.com |date=January 25, 2010 |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716012123/http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=43&item=870 |archive-date=July 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMain Cabin passengers receive complimentary snacks and non-alcoholic drinks on all flights {{convert|250|mi|km}} or longer. Alcoholic beverages are also available for purchase. Complimentary meals and alcoholic drinks are provided on long-haul international flights as well as selected transcontinental domestic flights, such as between New York\u2013JFK and Seattle, San Francisco, Los Angeles, and San Diego.<ref name=\"delta.com-main-cabin-features\">{{cite web|title=Economy Class Flights: Main Cabin|url=http://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/onboard-experience/main-cabin-economy-class.html|website=Delta.com|publisher=Delta Air Lines|accessdate=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513073135/http://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/onboard-experience/main-cabin-economy-class.html|archive-date=May 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.delta.com/delta-debuts-free-main-cabin-meals-12-markets | title=Delta debuts free Main Cabin meals in 12 markets | first=Catherine | last=Simmons | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=February 16, 2017 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161635/https://news.delta.com/delta-debuts-free-main-cabin-meals-12-markets | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> As part of Delta's Flight Fuel [[buy on board]] program, meals are available for purchase on other North American flights {{convert|900|mi|km}} or longer.<ref name=\"delta.com-main-cabin-features\" />\n\nDelta operated a different buy on board program between 2003 and 2005.<ref>Alexander, Keith L. \"[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2005/03/27/TRG1CBUD291.DTL Passengers find buy-on-board food hard to digest \u2013 Airlines are starting to feed fliers again].\" ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''. Sunday March 27, 2005. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103210907/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F2005%2F03%2F27%2FTRG1CBUD291.DTL |date=January 3, 2009 }}</ref><ref>Morales, Tatiana. \"[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/07/04/earlyshow/living/travel/main561770.shtml Buy On-Board Meals?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212001519/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/07/04/earlyshow/living/travel/main561770.shtml |date=December 12, 2008 }}.\" ''[[The Early Show]]''/''[[CBS News]]''. July 7, 2003. Retrieved on September 16, 2009.</ref> The previous program had items from differing providers, depending on the origin and destination of the flight.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20031002224732/http://www.delta.com/travel/during_flight/dining/food_for_sale_062003/index.jsp Food Sales Test].\" Delta Air Lines. October 2, 2003. Retrieved on September 16, 2009.</ref><ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20040218160420/http://www.delta.com/travel/during_flight/dining/food_for_sale_062003/index.jsp Food Sales].\" Delta Air Lines. February 18, 2004. Retrieved on September 16, 2009.</ref> Prices ranged up to $10 (${{inflation|USD|10|2004<!--Using 2004-->|r=2}} when adjusted for inflation). The airline started the service on a few selected flights in July 2003, and the meal service was initially offered on 400 flights.<ref name=WeberFreefoodagain>\"[http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Mar/10/bz/bz11p.html Delta restoring free food service] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102034919/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Mar/10/bz/bz11p.html |date=January 2, 2015 }}.\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at ''[[The Honolulu Advertiser]]''. March 10, 2005. Retrieved on December 31, 2012.</ref> Delta ended this buy on board program in 2005; instead, Delta began offering snacks at no extra charge on flights over 90 minutes to most U.S. domestic flights and some flights to the Caribbean and Latin America. Beginning in mid-March 2005 the airline planned to stop providing pillows on flights within the 48 contiguous U.S. states, Bermuda, Canada, the Caribbean, and Central America. In addition, the airline increased the price of alcoholic beverages on Delta mainline flights from $4 (${{inflation|USD|4|2005|r=2}} when adjusted for inflation) to $5 (${{inflation|USD|5|2005|r=2}} when adjusted for inflation); the increase in alcohol prices did not occur on Song flights.<ref name=WeberFreefoodagain/>\n\n===Basic Economy===\n[[Basic Economy]] is a basic version of Main Cabin, offering the same services with fewer flexibility options for a lower price.<ref name=\"CabinRefresh\"/> Examples of fewer flexibility options include no ticket changes, no paid or complimentary upgrades regardless of frequent-flier status, and only having a seat assigned at check-in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/onboard-experience/main-cabin/basic-economy.html|title=Basic Economy : Delta Air Lines|publisher=|access-date=April 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408095522/http://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/traveling-with-us/onboard-experience/main-cabin/basic-economy.html|archive-date=April 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==On-board amenities==\n\n===Wi-Fi===\nOn August 5, 2008, Delta announced it would be installing the [[Aircell]] mobile broadband network, [[Gogo Inflight Internet]], which enables customers traveling with [[Wi-Fi]] enabled devices, such as laptops, smartphones, and tablets, to access the Internet for a fee. Gogo was initially offered on Delta's fleet of McDonnell Douglas MD-88 and MD-90 aircraft but has expanded to the remaining domestic fleet, as well as Delta Connection aircraft with a first class cabin.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dayton/news/2010/11/29/delta-adds-wi-fi-on-regional-jets.html | title=Delta Air Lines adds Wi-Fi on regional jets | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=November 29, 2010 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921154058/https://www.bizjournals.com/dayton/news/2010/11/29/delta-adds-wi-fi-on-regional-jets.html | archive-date=September 21, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDelta has the largest fleet of Wi-Fi equipped aircraft in the world.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jon | last=Swartz | url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/2011-02-01-facebook-inflight-wifi_N.htm | title=Airlines Offer Free In-Flight Facebook | work=[[USA Today]] | date=February 1, 2011 | access-date=August 27, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218020617/http://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/2011-02-01-facebook-inflight-wifi_N.htm | archive-date=February 18, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The airline introduced its first inflight Wi-Fi on international routes to Tokyo from Los Angeles and Atlanta in March 2014, and stated its intent to offer the service on all transoceanic flight routes by the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Mutzabaugh | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2014/03/26/delta-debuts-international-wi-fi-on-its-boeing-747s/6903427/ | title=Delta debuts international Wi-Fi on its Boeing 747s | work=[[USA Today]] | date=March 26, 2014 | access-date=August 27, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710210535/https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2014/03/26/delta-debuts-international-wi-fi-on-its-boeing-747s/6903427/ | archive-date=July 10, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Even though Delta had announced the retirement of its 747 fleet, all Delta 747s were Wi-Fi equipped before their withdrawal. Delta is currently installing Wi-Fi on the [[Boeing 777]] fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.delta.com/delta-wi-fi-across-trans-atlantic-fleet-gets-customers-online|title=Delta Wi-Fi across trans-Atlantic fleet gets customers online|date=February 3, 2016|access-date=March 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411052743/http://news.delta.com/delta-wi-fi-across-trans-atlantic-fleet-gets-customers-online|archive-date=April 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the company announced plans to eventually offer free Wi-Fi on all flights.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-taking-free-wi-fi-for-a-spin-11557410441 | title=Delta to Test Free Wi-Fi on Domestic Flights | first=Alison | last=Sider | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=May 9, 2019 | url-access=subscription | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715224332/https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-taking-free-wi-fi-for-a-spin-11557410441 | archive-date=July 15, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/airlines-airports/delta/delta-free-wifi-flights | title=Delta Is Planning to Have Free Wi-Fi on Flights | first=CAILEY | last=RIZZO | work=[[Travel + Leisure]] | date=March 13, 2019 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014953/https://www.travelandleisure.com/airlines-airports/delta/delta-free-wifi-flights | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===In-flight entertainment===\n====History====\nIn the 1960s, audio programming was introduced where passengers wore headphones consisting of hollow tubes piping in music. These were installed in some Delta aircraft. Some early wide-bodied aircraft, including the [[Lockheed L-1011]], [[Boeing 767-200#767-200|Boeing 767-200]], and [[767-300#767-300|Boeing 767-300]] fleet, had movies projected onto the cabin bulkhead. Also during the late 1980s and early 1990s, [[CRT display|CRT]] monitors over the aisles were added to the 757 fleet, making them the first narrowbody aircraft to feature video entertainment. The MD-90 introduced Delta's first [[In-flight entertainment|IFE system]] with [[liquid crystal display|LCD]] monitors in 1995, and the 777 introduced Delta's first in-seat video system in 1999, initially using the [[Rockwell Collins]] Total Entertainment System. Delta's first all-digital IFE system with AVOD (Panasonic eFX) was first introduced in 2003 on Delta's former low-cost subsidiary, Song. The Rockwell Collins IFE system on the 777s was replaced by the Panasonic eFX system in 2007, followed by the Panasonic eX2 in 2011. The Panasonic eFX and eX2 systems are trademarked by Delta as \"Delta on Demand\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.delta.com/delta-brings-award-winning-flight-experience-skies-new-%E2%80%9Csky360%C2%B0-delta%E2%80%9D-new-york-city | title=Delta Brings Award-Winning In-Flight Experience from the Skies to the New \"SKY360\u00b0 by Delta\" in New York City | publisher=Delta Air Lines | date=October 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2010, Delta installed the Panasonic eFX AVOD system in Economy on six 767-300ERs that are used on routes that are 12 hours or longer.<ref name=\"flyertalk.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.flyertalk.com/forum/delta-skymiles/1007665-767-international-fleet-seating-update.html |title=767 International Fleet seating update |publisher=Flyertalk.com |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723175955/http://www.flyertalk.com/forum/delta-skymiles/1007665-767-international-fleet-seating-update.html |archive-date=July 23, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Delta also announced it would be installing AVOD in Economy class on all Boeing 767-300ER and 747 aircraft over the next 3 years.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delta-to-invest-in-customer-experience-fleet-efficiency-82600907.html | title=Delta to Invest in Customer Experience, Fleet Efficiency | publisher=[[PR Newswire]] | date=January 25, 2010 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014954/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/delta-to-invest-in-customer-experience-fleet-efficiency-82600907.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2010, Delta announced that it would be the launch customer of the new eX2 AVOD system with the Eco 9i Integrated Smart Monitor, a new ultra-lightweight IFE system by Panasonic Avionics Corporation and [[Zodiac Seats U.S.]]<ref name=\"panasonic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/blogs/runway-girl/2010/07/delta-air-lines-to-launch-pana.html |title=BREAKING: Delta Air Lines to launch Panasonic's Fusion (Smart!!!) |work=Flight International |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730173402/http://www.flightglobal.com/blogs/runway-girl/2010/07/delta-air-lines-to-launch-pana.html |archivedate=July 30, 2010 }}</ref> The systems have been installed on the entire 747-400 fleet as of October 2012, and are currently being installed on the 767-300ER fleet (except for the six aircraft previously retrofitted with the eFX system in 2010).<ref name=\"ifec\">{{cite web |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/07/28/345502/delta-to-launch-integrated-ifecseat-from-panasonic.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102211511/http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-to-launch-integrated-ifecseat-from-panasonic-345502/ |archivedate=November 2, 2011 |title=Delta to launch integrated IFEC/seat from Panasonic, Weber |work=Flight International |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> A different version of the Integrated Smart Monitor developed by Panasonic Avionics Corporation and [[BE Aerospace]] was installed on the Airbus A330 fleet. These seats were also installed on all Boeing 757-300, [[Boeing 737 Next Generation#737-900ER|Boeing 737-900ER]], [[Airbus A321]] and select Boeing 757-200 domestic aircraft, and replaced the existing seats and monitors on the international Boeing 757-200 fleet. The previous seats on the [[International flight|international]] 757-200 fleet have been placed on select [[Domestic flight|domestic]] 757-200 aircraft, mainly ones flying between Hawaii and the U.S. mainland.\n\nIn 2012, Delta began replacing the overhead CRT monitors on the pre-merger Delta 757-200 fleet with new LCD monitors.<ref name=\"pvt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.flyertalk.com/forum/delta-skymiles/1239128-no-ptvs-regular-pmdl-752s-new-lcds-instead-2.html |title=No PTVs for regular PMDL 752s, new LCDs instead |publisher=Flyertalk.com |accessdate=April 5, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328191238/http://www.flyertalk.com/forum/delta-skymiles/1239128-no-ptvs-regular-pmdl-752s-new-lcds-instead-2.html |archive-date=March 28, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> This was completed in late 2012.\n\nThe 767-400ER fleet initially featured LCDs over the aisles, but were replaced in 2009 by the Panasonic eFX AVOD system when the last of the 767-400ERs were converted from domestic to international use. CRT projectors were originally featured in economy class on [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300s]], with the international 767-300ERs also featuring ceiling-mounted CRT displays over the aisles, which have since replaced by LCD monitors, and are now in the process of being converted to the eFX2 AVOD system.\n\nWhen Delta's ex-[[Trans World Airlines|TWA]] [[ETOPS]] 757s were first delivered, they featured a system made by Sony Transcom (a former subsidiary of [[Sony]] now sold to [[Rockwell Collins]]) system that was factory installed for TWA. The system featured overhead drop-down [[LCD]] monitors similar to Delta's non-Transcon 737-800s and 757-300s. Delta replaced the Sony Transcom system with the Panasonic eFX system featuring in-seat video and AVOD at the same time as the new BusinessElite seats and slimline economy class seats were installed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.delta.com/2007/08/31/enhancing-the-entertainment-experience/#comment-122 |title=Enhancing the Entertainment Experience |author=Chris Babb |date=September 2, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514010347/http://blog.delta.com/2007/08/31/enhancing-the-entertainment-experience/ |archivedate=May 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n====Current fleet==== \nAudio and video are available on all aircraft except for the [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|MD-88]], [[Boeing 717]], [[McDonnell Douglas MD-90|MD-90]], and [[Delta Connection]] aircraft. [[Boeing 777-200ER]], [[Boeing 777-200LR|777-200LR]], along with [[Boeing 767#767-300|767-300]] and [[Airbus A330|A330]] aircraft that have completed cabin modifications, feature the Panasonic eX2 system. Compared to the older eFX system, this offers greater storage capacity, as well as lighter and larger personal video screens.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.shephard.co.uk/Inflight/default.aspx?Action=-1000945703&ID=32c250df-e45e-42d1-9747-bac853a0dd69|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107110406/http://www.shephard.co.uk/Inflight/default.aspx?Action=-1000945703&ID=32c250df-e45e-42d1-9747-bac853a0dd69|archivedate=November 7, 2007|title=US majors get with the cabin-upgrade programme|accessdate=December 16, 2006|publisher=Shepard Group|date=December 16, 2006}}</ref> [[Boeing 767#767-400ER|Boeing 767-400ER]] aircraft, selected [[Boeing 757#757-200|757-200]] aircraft, as well as the remaining internationally configured [[Boeing 767-300ER#767-300ER|Boeing 767-300ER]] aircraft that have not completed cabin modifications, use the [[Panasonic Avionics Corporation|Panasonic]] eFX AVOD system.\n\nDomestic [[Boeing 767#767-300|Boeing 767-300s]], [[Boeing 737 Next Generation#737-700|Boeing 737-700s]], as well as selected [[Transcontinental flight|transcontinental]] [[Boeing 757#757-200|Boeing 757-200s]] and selected [[Boeing 737 Next Generation#737-800|Boeing 737-800s]] using the Panasonic eFX system, also feature live television via [[Dish Network]] in both first class and economy. Some [[Boeing 737 Next Generation#737-800|Boeing 737-800s]], as well as all [[Boeing 757#757-300|Boeing 757-300s]] feature systems with drop-down LCD displays below the overhead bins.<ref>{{cite web |last=No |first=Brisan |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/brisan/2242036182/ |title=Delta 737-800 Cabin {{pipe}} Flickr |publisher=Flickr.com |date=December 9, 2007 |accessdate=April 5, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113132842/http://www.flickr.com/photos/brisan/2242036182/ |archive-date=November 13, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{Outdated as of | 2017 | topic = Recent installation of IFE}}\n\nAll aircraft with AVOD, except for the [[Airbus A220|A220 (formerly CSeries)]], feature Panasonic's iXplor moving map program. 737-800s with overhead video and the coach sections of 767-300ER aircraft with overhead video feature the [[Rockwell Collins]] Airshow moving map, which is often shown during takeoff and landing. Other aircraft formerly equipped with the Rockwell Collins Airshow moving map included the [[Lockheed L-1011 TriStar|Lockheed L-1011]]-250 and -500, [[McDonnell Douglas MD-11|MD-11]], and [[Boeing 767#767-400ER|Boeing 767-400ER]] and [[Boeing 777|777-200ER]]. The L-1011 and MD-11 fleet have since been retired, while the 767-400ER and 777-200ER have since had their Airshow systems replaced by the Panasonic iXplor system built into the eFX and eX2 AVOD systems.\n\n===Delta Sky Magazine===\n[http://www.deltaskymag.com Delta Sky Magazine] and its online edition is an airline magazine published by MSP Communications in Minneapolis, Minnesota. It is available in every seat on all routes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://deltaskymag.com/Magazine.aspx | title=The Magazine | publisher=Delta Sky Magazine | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014954/http://deltaskymag.com/Magazine.aspx | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Reward programs==\n===SkyMiles===\n{{Main|SkyMiles}}\nSkyMiles is the [[frequent flyer program]] for Delta Air Lines. Miles do not expire but accounts may be deactivated by Delta in certain cases, such as the death of a program member or fraudulent activity.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/skymiles/program-resources/program-rules.html | title=Membership Guide & Program Rules | publisher=Delta Air Lines | access-date=February 6, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206011531/https://www.delta.com/content/www/en_US/skymiles/program-resources/program-rules.html | archive-date=February 6, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Delta Sky Club===\n[[File:New Delta Sky Club (29840678206).jpg|thumb|A SkyClub in Concourse B at [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport]]]]\n\nDelta Sky Club is the branding name of Delta's airport lounges. Membership is available through an annual membership that can be purchased with either money or miles. International passengers traveling in Delta One class get free access. Membership can also be granted through top level Delta status or by being an American Express card holder with certain exceptions. As of January, 2019, Delta no longer offers single day passes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delta's Sky Bonus |url=http://www.odysseymediagroup.com/nan/Editorial-Airlines-And-Airports.asp?ReportID=30419 |accessdate=6 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015308/http://www.odysseymediagroup.com/nan/Editorial-Airlines-And-Airports.asp?ReportID=30419 |archive-date=February 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFeatures vary by location, but generally include free drinks (including alcoholic beverages), snacks, and reading material. Wi-Fi is free for members and guests and is mostly provided in the US by AT&T.\n\nOriginally, Delta's membership-based airport clubs were called Crown Room lounges, with Northwest's called WorldClubs.\n\n===SkyBonus===\nOn November 27, 2001, Delta Air Lines launched SkyBonus,<ref name=\"skybonus\">{{cite web |title=Airlines & Airports - Delta New SkyBonus Program Rewards Small-To-Medium Sized Businesses |url=http://www.odysseymediagroup.com/nan/Editorial-Airlines-And-Airports.asp?ReportID=30419 |website=www.odysseymediagroup.com |accessdate=2 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015308/http://www.odysseymediagroup.com/nan/Editorial-Airlines-And-Airports.asp?ReportID=30419 |archive-date=February 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a program aimed toward small-to-medium businesses spending between $5,000 and $500,000 annually on air travel.<ref name=\"bonus press\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/skybonus-becomes-official-business-loyalty-program-for-delta-air-france-klm-and-alitalia-in-north-america-117158528.html|title=SkyBonus Becomes Official Business Loyalty Program for Delta, Air France, KLM and Alitalia in North America|publisher=Delta Airlines|accessdate=January 31, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606031745/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/skybonus-becomes-official-business-loyalty-program-for-delta-air-france-klm-and-alitalia-in-north-america-117158528.html|archive-date=June 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Businesses can earn points toward free travel and upgrades, as well as Sky Club memberships and SkyMiles Silver Medallion status. Points are earned on paid travel based on a variety of fare amount paid, booking code, and place origin or destination.<ref name=\"faq\">{{cite web| title=Frequently Asked Questions| url=http://skybonus.delta.com/bizCoFAQ.sb| accessdate=January 31, 2013| publisher=Delta Airlines| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228172216/http://skybonus.delta.com/bizCoFAQ.sb| archive-date=December 28, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> While enrolled businesses are able to earn points toward free travel, the travelling passenger is still eligible to earn SkyMiles during his or her travel.<ref name=\"faq\"/>\n\nIn early 2010, Delta Air Lines merged its SkyBonus program with Northwest's similar Biz Perks program.<ref name=\"faq\" />\n\n==Corporate affairs==\n\n=== Finances ===\nFor the fiscal year 2018, Delta Air Lines reported earnings of US$5.1 billion, with an annual revenue of US$44.438 billion, an increase of 8.02% over the previous fiscal cycle. Its shares traded at over $48 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over US$39.182 billion in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delta Air Lines Revenue 2006-2018 {{!}} DAL |url=https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/DAL/delta-air-lines/revenue |website=www.macrotrends.net |access-date=April 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410120329/https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/DAL/delta-air-lines/revenue |archive-date=April 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Financial information for Delta, by year\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Revenue<br />in mil. USD$\n!scope=\"col\"| Net income<br />in mil. USD$\n!scope=\"col\"| Total assets<br />in mil. USD$\n!scope=\"col\"| Price per share<br />in USD$\n!scope=\"col\"| Employees\n!scope=\"col\"| Refs.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2005\n|16,480\n|\u22123,836\n|20,039\n|\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2005.pdf|title=2005 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204228/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2005.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2006\n|17,532\n|\u22126,205\n|19,622\n|\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2006.pdf|title=2006 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125205726/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2006.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2007\n|19,154\n|1,612\n|32,423\n|\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2007.pdf|title=2007 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204108/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2007.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2008\n|22,697\n|\u22128,922\n|45,084\n|8.76\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2008.pdf|title=2008 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204204/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2008.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2009\n|28,063\n| \u22121,237\n|43,789\n|6.97\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2009.pdf|title=2009 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204121/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2009.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2010\n|31,755\n| 593\n|43,188\n|11.66\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2010.pdf|title=2010 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204153/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2010.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2011\n|35,115\n|854\n|43,499\n|8.59\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2011.pdf|title=2011 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204045/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2011.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2012\n|36,670\n|1,009\n|44,550\n|9.321\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2012.pdf|title=2012 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126005413/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2012.pdf|archive-date=November 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2013\n|37,773\n|10,540\n|52,252\n|18.53\n|78,000\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2013.pdf|title=2013 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204257/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2013.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2014\n|40,362\n|659\n|54,005\n|35.12\n|80,000\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2014.pdf|title=2014 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125205738/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2014.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2015\n|40,704\n| 4,526\n|53,134\n|43.42\n|83,000\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2015.pdf|title=2015 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126005420/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2015.pdf|archive-date=November 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2016\n|39,639\n|4,373\n|51,261\n|41.11\n|84,000\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2016.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204032/http://www.annualreports.com/HostedData/AnnualReportArchive/d/NYSE_DAL_2016.pdf|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2017\n|41,244\n|3,577\n|53,292\n|48.52\n|87,000\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-announces-december-quarter-and-full-year-2017-profit|title=Delta Air Lines announces December quarter and full year 2017 profit|website=Delta News Hub|access-date=2018-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125204505/https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-announces-december-quarter-and-full-year-2017-profit|archive-date=November 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2018\n|44,438\n|3,935\n|60,270\n|47.83\n|89,000\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Delta Air Lines announces December quarter and full year 2018 profit |url=https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-announces-december-quarter-and-full-year-2018-profit |website=Delta News Hub |access-date=April 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410120344/https://news.delta.com/delta-air-lines-announces-december-quarter-and-full-year-2018-profit |archive-date=April 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Document |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27904/000002790419000003/dal1231201810k.htm |website=www.sec.gov |page=10 |access-date=April 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410120330/https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27904/000002790419000003/dal1231201810k.htm |archive-date=April 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n|}\n\n===Personnel===\nBetween its mainline operation and subsidiaries, and as of March 2015, Delta employs nearly 80,000 people.<ref name=\"statsfacts\"/> [[Ed Bastian]] is the current Chief Executive Officer and has served in this position since May 2, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delta.com/bio-ed-bastian-chief-executive-officer|title=Bio: Ed Bastian, Chief Executive Officer|website=Delta News Hub|access-date=2018-06-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143459/https://news.delta.com/bio-ed-bastian-chief-executive-officer|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Joanne Smith]] is Executive Vice President and Chief Human Resources Officer responsible for the oversight and support of personnel needs at Delta. She was appointed on October 1, 2014, replacing Mike Campbell.<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-human-resources-and-labor-executive-to-retire-1409165875 |title=Delta Human Resources and Labor Executive to Retire |last=Carey |first=Susan |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=August 27, 2014 |url-access=subscription |access-date=March 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709134947/https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-human-resources-and-labor-executive-to-retire-1409165875 |archive-date=July 9, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDelta's 14,500 mainline pilots are represented by the [[Air Line Pilots Association, International]] and are the union's largest pilot group.<ref name=\"WSJESTERL\"/><ref>{{cite web | title=ALPA's Pilot Groups | publisher=[[Air Line Pilots Association, International]] | date=January\u2013February 2012 | url=http://www.alpa.org/Home/WhoWeAre/PilotGroups/tabid/2239/Default.aspx | access-date=January 2, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228084326/http://www.alpa.org/Home/WhoWeAre/PilotGroups/tabid/2239/Default.aspx | archive-date=December 28, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company's approximately 180 flight dispatchers are represented by the Professional Airline Flight Control Association (PAFCA).<ref>{{cite web |title=PAFCA - Professional Airline Flight Control Association |url=http://www.pafca.org/faq.asp |accessdate=29 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416085033/http://www.pafca.org/faq.asp |archive-date=April 16, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Not counting the pilots and flight dispatchers, Delta is the only one of the five [[List of largest airlines in North America|largest airlines in the United States]], and one of only two in the top 9 (the other being JetBlue), whose non-pilot USA domestic staff is entirely non-union.<ref name=\"WSJESTERL\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304474804576369762641111264#articleTabs%3Darticle | last=Esterl | first=Mike | title=Labor Board Broadens Delta Probe | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=June 6, 2011 | url-access=subscription | access-date=August 3, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805100641/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304474804576369762641111264#articleTabs%3Darticle | archive-date=August 5, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:DeltaAirLinesHQAtlantaGA.jpg|thumb|Delta Air Lines headquarters in Atlanta]]\n\n===Headquarters and offices===\nDelta's corporate headquarters is located on a corporate campus on the northern boundary of Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport, within the city limits of Atlanta.<ref name=\"schmidt\">{{cite news| author=William E. Schmidt| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/16/us/delta-loyalists-alarmed-and-bruised-by-mishaps.html| title=Delta Loyalists Alarmed And Bruised by Mishaps| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=July 16, 1987| url-access=subscription| access-date=February 7, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625141845/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/16/us/delta-loyalists-alarmed-and-bruised-by-mishaps.html| archive-date=June 25, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.delta.com/help/contact_us/corporate_information/index.jsp Contact Corporate] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530042524/http://www.delta.com/help/contact_us/corporate_information/index.jsp |date=May 30, 2008 }}.\" ''Delta Air Lines''. Retrieved October 17, 2008.</ref><ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080824014251/http://apps.atlantaga.gov/citydir/dpcd/maps/zoning_sheet_14-128.pdf Zoning Ordinance of Atlanta, Georgia Sheet No. 14-128].\" () ''[[Atlanta, Georgia|City of Atlanta]]''. Retrieved October 17, 2008.</ref> This location has served as Delta's headquarters since 1941, when the company relocated its corporate offices from [[Monroe, Louisiana]] to [[Greater Atlanta]].<ref>Markiewicz, David. \"[http://www.ajc.com/business/issues-change-but-chamber-222782.html Issues change, but Chamber rolls on 150 years later] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604115046/http://www.ajc.com/business/issues-change-but-chamber-222782.html |date=June 4, 2011 }}.\" ''[[Atlanta Journal Constitution]]''. Wednesday December 2, 2009. Retrieved on December 27, 2009.</ref><ref>\"[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB328DD4FBC7A73&p_field_direct-0=document_id Delta Air Lines Started as Crop-Dusting Service] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825074331/http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB328DD4FBC7A73&p_field_direct-0=document_id |date=August 25, 2018 }}\". [[Associated Press]] at ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''. September 1, 1988. 11A. Retrieved on December 27, 2009.</ref> The crop dusting division of Delta remained headquartered in Monroe until Delta ceased crop dusting in 1966.<ref name=journey/> Before 1981, the Delta corporate campus, an {{convert|80|acre|ha|adj=on}} plot of land in proximity to the old Hartsfield Airport terminal, was outside the City of Atlanta limits in [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]. On August 3, 1981, the [[Atlanta City Council]] approved the annexation of {{convert|141|acres|ha}} of land, an area containing the Delta headquarters. As of 1981 Delta would have had to begin paying $200,000 annually to the City of Atlanta in taxes. In September 1981, the airline sued the city, challenging the annexation on the basis of the constitutionality of the 1960 City of Atlanta annexation of the Hartsfield old terminal.<ref name=DeltaSuingCityATL>\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19810902&id=uL4IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IUQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4096,105025 Delta suing City of Atlanta].\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at ''[[Rome News-Tribune]]''. Wednesday September 2, 1981. p. 10A. Retrieved from [[Google News]] (6 of 29) on December 19, 2013.</ref> The City of Atlanta was only permitted to annex areas that are adjacent to areas already in the Atlanta city limits.<ref name=DeltaSuingCityATL/>\n\nIn addition to hosting Delta's corporate headquarters, Hartsfield-Jackson is also the home of [[Delta TechOps]], the airline's primary maintenance, repair, and overhaul arm and the largest full-service airline MRO in North America, specializing in engines, components, airframe, and line maintenance.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/suppliers/delta-techops | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220024534/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/suppliers/delta-techops | archivedate=December 20, 2013 | title=Capa Centre For Aviation | accessdate=May 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDelta maintains a large presence in the [[Minneapolis \u2013 Saint Paul|Twin Cities]], with over 12,000 employees<ref name=\"mpr\">{{cite news | url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/01/29/delta-minnesota-headquarters/ | title=Delta Air Lines officially opens Minnesota headquarters | work=Minnesota Public Radio News | publisher=Minnesota.publicradio.org | date=January 29, 2010 | accessdate=July 7, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726132134/http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/01/29/delta-minnesota-headquarters | archive-date=July 26, 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref> in the region as well as significant corporate support functions housed in the Minneapolis area, including the company's information technology divisional offices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=43&item=358 |title=MAC Approves Agreement with Delta for 10,000 Minnesota Jobs and 400 Daily Departures from Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul Hub |publisher=News.delta.com |date=January 26, 2009 |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720070151/http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=43&item=358 |archive-date=July 20, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Corporate identity===\n[[File:Delta Air Lines A330-323 (N809NW) landing at Amsterdam Airport Schiphol (1).jpg|thumb|An Airbus A330-300 painted in Delta's current livery, \"Upward & Onward\"]]\nDelta's logo, often called the \"widget\", was originally unveiled in 1959. Its triangle shape is taken from the Greek letter [[delta (letter)|delta]], and recalls the airline's origins in the [[Mississippi Delta]].<ref name=\"Mouawad1\">{{cite news | first=Jad | last=Mouawad | title=On Jet Exteriors, a Parade of Vanilla | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/24/business/on-the-exterior-of-jetliners-a-parade-of-plain-vanilla.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 23, 2011 | url-access=subscription | access-date=February 7, 2017 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DQw643us?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/24/business/on-the-exterior-of-jetliners-a-parade-of-plain-vanilla.html?_r=0 | archive-date=January 5, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> It is also said to be reminiscent of the swept-wing design of the DC-8, Delta's first jet aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.famouslogos.us/delta-airlines-logo/ |title= Delta Air Lines Logo |accessdate= July 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170313124416/http://www.famouslogos.us/delta-airlines-logo/ |archive-date= March 13, 2017 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nDelta's current [[Aircraft livery|livery]] is called \"Upward & Onward\". It features a white fuselage with the company's name in blue lettering, and a widget on the vertical stabilizer. Delta introduced its current livery in 2007 as part of a re-branding after it emerged from bankruptcy. The new livery consists of four colors, while the old one (called \"colors in motion\") used eight. This meant the switch saved the airline money by removing one day from each aircraft's painting cycle. The airline took four years to repaint all of its aircraft into the current scheme, including aircraft inherited from Northwest Airlines.<ref name=\"Mouawad1\"/>\n\n===Environmental initiatives===\nIn 2008, Delta Air Lines was given an award from the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]'s Design for the Environment (DfE) program for their use of PreKote, a more environmentally friendly, non-hexavalent chromium surface pretreatment on its aircraft, replacing hazardous chemicals formerly used to improve paint adhesion and prevent corrosion. In addition, PreKote reduces water usage by two-thirds and reduces wastewater treatment.\n\nPreKote is also saving money by reducing the time needed to paint each airplane. With time savings of eight to ten percent, it will save an estimated more than $1 million annually.<ref name=\"Delta Air Lines News Release\">{{cite web|title=Delta Air Lines Accepts EPA Award for Use of Nontoxic Materials on Aircraft|url=http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=43&item=22|work=Delta Air Lines News Release|publisher=Delta Air Lines|accessdate=March 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929110225/http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=43&item=22|archive-date=September 29, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n===Deltalina===\n{{Main|Deltalina}}\nAs part of the re-branding project, a [[safety video]] featuring a flight attendant showed up on YouTube in early 2008, getting over 1 million views and the attention of news outlets, specifically for the video's tone mixed with the serious safety message. The flight attendant, Katherine Lee, was dubbed \"Deltalina\" by a member of FlyerTalk for her resemblance to [[Angelina Jolie]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.ajc.com/news/who-deltalina-flashback-2008/5WbYDzscytXwoDPjI91uwK/ | title=Who is Deltalina? Flashback to 2008 | first=Jennifer | last=Brett | work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] | date=July 16, 2017 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115234403/https://www.ajc.com/news/who-deltalina-flashback-2008/5WbYDzscytXwoDPjI91uwK/ | archive-date=November 15, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/2008/03/deltas-new-safe/ | title=Delta's New Sexy Safety Starlet | first=Joe | last=Brown | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date=March 26, 2008 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002215223/https://www.wired.com/2008/03/deltas-new-safe/ | archive-date=October 2, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> Delta had considered several styles for its current safety video, including animation, before opting for a video presenting a flight attendant speaking to the audience. The video was filmed on a former Song Airlines Boeing 757-200.<ref>\"[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,340624,00.html Delta's Red-Headed Flight Attendant a Hit on YouTube in Airline's Safety Video] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515233348/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,340624,00.html |date=May 15, 2008 }}.\" [[Associated Press]] at ''[[Fox News]]''. Sunday March 23, 2008. Retrieved on August 24, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\nThe following are major accidents and incidents that occurred on Delta mainline aircraft. For Northwest Airlines incidents, see [[Northwest Airlines accidents and incidents]]. For Delta Connection incidents, see [[Delta Connection#Incidents and accidents|Delta Connection incidents and accidents]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Delta Air Lines reported incidents'''\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Flight\n!rowspan=2|Date\n!rowspan=2|Aircraft\n!rowspan=2|Location\n!rowspan=2|Description\n!colspan=5|Injuries\n|-\n!Fatal\n!Serious\n!Minor\n!Uninjured\n!Ground\n|-\n|4<ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=Accident Stinson Model A NC14599, 14 Aug 1935 |url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=162890 |website=aviation-safety.net |accessdate=November 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109081028/https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=162890 |archive-date=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|August 14, 1935\n|[[Stinson Model A]]\n|[[Gilmer, Texas]]\n|En route to [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], the left engine was ripped off of the aircraft due to a propeller blade failure. The pilot attempted to make an emergency landing in a cotton field, but lost control and crashed.\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|N/A<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19470422-0 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-3C NC49657 Columbus, GA |website=aviation-safety.net |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324020340/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19470422-0 |archive-date=March 24, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|April 22, 1947\n|[[Douglas DC-3]]\n|[[Columbus, Georgia]]\n|A [[Vultee BT-13]], owned by the [[Tuskegee University|Tuskegee Aviation Institute]], landed on top of a Delta DC-3, which was flying from Macon to Columbus.\n|9 (8 on DC-3)\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|705<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19480310-1 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-4 NC37478 Chicago Municipal Airport, IL (MDW) |website=aviation-safety.net |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DqAXjyon?url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19480310-1 |archive-date=January 21, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|March 10, 1948\n|[[Douglas DC-4|DC-4]]\n|[[Chicago Midway International Airport|Chicago]]\n|Crashed near Chicago Municipal (Midway) Airport shortly after takeoff while en route to Miami. Officials determined that longitudinal control of the airplane was lost resulting in the crash. The cause for the loss of control remains undetermined.\n|12\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|318<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19530517-0 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DST-318 (DC-3) N28345 Marshall, TX |website=aviation-safety.net |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321080254/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19530517-0 |archive-date=March 21, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|May 17, 1953\n|DC-3\n|[[Marshall, Texas]]\n|Crashed {{convert|13|mi|km}} east of Marshall, Texas. The flight, which originated from [[Dallas Love Field]], was on approach to [[Shreveport Regional Airport|Shreveport, Louisiana]]. The crash was attributed to adverse weather conditions with a thunderstorm in the area.\n|19\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1903\n|May 23, 1960\n|[[Convair 880]]\n|[[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta]]\n|Crashed during a training exercise in Atlanta. The aircraft stalled and crashed killing all four crew members.\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|9877<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19670330-0 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-8-51 N802E New Orleans, LA |website=aviation-safety.net |access-date=January 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060302123011/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19670330-0 |archive-date=March 2, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|March 30, 1967\n|DC-8\n|[[Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport|New Orleans]]\n|Crashed during a training exercise near [[Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport|New Orleans]]. The improper use of flight and power controls by both instructor and the Captain-trainee during a simulated two-engine out landing approach, resulted in the loss of control. The aircraft crashed into a residential area, destroying several homes and a motel complex and killing 13 people on the ground.<ref>{{cite web | title=Crashed short, Delta Air Lines, Inc., DC-8, N802E, New Orleans International Airport, Kenner, Louisiana, March 30, 1967 | url=https://www.fss.aero/accident-reports/dvdfiles/US/1967-03-30-US.pdf | publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]] | date=December 20, 1967}}</ref>\n|6\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|13\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 9570|9570]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19720530-0 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-9-14 N3305L Fort Worth-Greater Southwest Airport, TX (GSW) |website=aviation-safety.net |access-date=February 1, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060225104124/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19720530-0 |archive-date=February 25, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|May 30, 1972\n|[[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]]\n|[[Greater Southwest International Airport|Fort Worth, Texas]]\n|A training exercise, crashed during landing procedures in Fort Worth, Texas. The probable cause of the accident was wake turbulence resulting from a [[touch-and-go landing]] moments before of American Airlines Flight 1114, operated using a [[DC-10]]. The right wing hit the ground causing a fire resulting in the aircraft being written off.\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|954<ref>{{cite web |url=http://libraryonline.erau.edu/online-full-text/ntsb/aircraft-accident-reports/AAR73-15.pdf |title=NTSB Report AAR73-15 |format=PDF |access-date=November 19, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507064053/http://libraryonline.erau.edu/online-full-text/ntsb/aircraft-accident-reports/AAR73-15.pdf |archive-date=May 7, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|December 20, 1972\n|Convair 880\n|[[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago]]\n|The Delta CV-880 taxied across runway 27L in heavy fog. At the same time, [[North Central Airlines]] Flight 575, a [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]]-31, took off from the same runway. The aircraft [[1972 Chicago-O'Hare runway collision|collided]].\n|10 (all on DC-9-31)\n|0\n|17 (severity unknown)\n|101\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 723|723]]\n|July 31, 1973\n|[[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]]\n|[[Boston Logan International Airport|Boston]]\n|Crashed into a seawall. Contributing to the accident was a defective flight deck instrument giving the crew misleading guidance during the instrument approach in visibility less than a half mile with {{convert|500|ft|m|adj=on}} cloud ceilings. 89 occupants died including [[Leopold Chouinard]], who died from burns months after the accident, leaving no survivors.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/08/01/archives/88-die-one-critically-hurt-in-jet-crash-in-boston-fog-83-passengers.html | title=88 Die, One. Critically Hurt In Jet Crash in Boston Fog | first=Robert | last=Reinhold | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=August 1, 1973 | url-access=subscription | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119053102/http://www.nytimes.com/1973/08/01/archives/88-die-one-critically-hurt-in-jet-crash-in-boston-fog-83-passengers.html | archive-date=January 19, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.airsafe.com/events/airlines/delta.htm | title=Fatal Events Since 1970 for Delta Air Lines | publisher=Airsafe.com | access-date=October 13, 2007 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66UDRgGZJ?url=http://www.airsafe.com/events/airlines/delta.htm | archive-date=March 27, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|89\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 516|516]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19731127-1 | title=ASN Aircraft accident McDonnell Douglas DC-9-32 N3323L Chattanooga Municipal Airport, TN (CHA) | website=aviation-safety.net | access-date=December 23, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606072009/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19731127-1 | archive-date=June 6, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|November 27, 1973\n|[[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]]\n|[[Chattanooga Metropolitan Airport|Chattanooga]]\n|Crashed into approach lights during a thunderstorm.<ref>{{cite web| title=Landed short, Delta Air Lines, Inc., McDonnell Douglas DC-9-32, N3323L, Chattanooga Municipal Airport, Chattanooga, Tennessee, November 27, 1973| url=https://www.fss.aero/accident-reports/dvdfiles/US/1973-11-27-US.pdf| publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]| date=November 8, 1974| access-date=July 27, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215233946/http://fss.aero/accident-reports/dvdfiles/US/1973-11-27-US.pdf| archive-date=December 15, 2010| url-status=live}}</ref>\n|0\n|4\n|75\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 1080|1080]]\n|April 12, 1977\n|Lockheed L-1011 Tristar\n|[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]]\n|Emergency landing at Los Angeles International Airport due to a jammed stabilizer during a flight from San Diego International Airport. The cause of the incident was a lack of greasing due to a high amount of water entering the metal bearings caused by weather factors. All 52 passengers and crew on board survived.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1978/10/08/the-saving-of-flight-1080/bc18f021-691d-4b19-8041-dc03a089bf6d/ | title=The Saving Of Flight 1080 | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=October 8, 1978 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093428/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1978/10/08/the-saving-of-flight-1080/bc18f021-691d-4b19-8041-dc03a089bf6d/ | archive-date=June 24, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|All\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 191|191]]\n|August 2, 1985\n|Lockheed L-1011 Tristar\n|[[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]]\n|On a [[Fort Lauderdale]]\u2013[[Dallas Fort Worth Metroplex|Dallas/Fort Worth]]- Los Angeles route, the plane crashed due to severe [[microburst]]-induced [[wind shear]]. One person on the ground was killed as the plane crossed a highway. The crash would later become the subject of a television movie. Numerous changes to pilot wind shear training, weather forecasting, and wind shear detection were made as a result of this crash.<ref name=\"changed\">{{cite episode | title=When Weather Changed History \u2013 Delta 191 Crash | url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/when-weather-changed-history/episode-7618610/348754// | network=[[The Weather Channel]] | series=[[When Weather Changed History]] | airdate=May 8, 2010 | access-date=July 17, 2019 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717125736/https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/when-weather-changed-history/episode-7618610/348754// | archivedate=July 17, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|136\n|13\n|13\n|2\n|1\n|-\n|37<ref>{{cite news | url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,965468,00.html | title=Wrong Track: Delta is blamed for a close call | first=Ed | last=Magnuson | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=September 14, 1987 | url-access=subscription | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161536/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,965468,00.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|July 8, 1987\n|Lockheed L-1011\n|North Atlantic Ocean\n|Near collision with a [[Continental Airlines]] 747 carrying 418 passengers and crew. Both the Delta (London-Cincinnati) and Continental (London-Newark) were heading to the U.S. with nearly 600 people total on both aircraft. The Delta flight strayed {{convert|60|mi|km}} off course to the south from its assigned \"C\" track during its flight and came within {{convert|30|ft|m}} of colliding with the 747 as the L-1011 flew under it in Canadian airspace, flying on the \"D\" track (there are five westbound and five eastbound tracks from the United States to the United Kingdom). Had the planes actually collided, it could have tied the [[Tenerife airport disaster]] as the deadliest aviation accident in history.\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|All\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 1141|1141]]\n|August 31, 1988\n|[[Boeing 727]]\n|[[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]]\n|Crashed after takeoff bound for Salt Lake City, Utah. The investigation stated the probable cause of this accident to be improper configuration of the flaps and leading edge slats.\n|14\n|26\n|50\n|18\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 1288|1288]]<ref>{{cite news | title=2 Killed as Engine Parts Pierce Cabin of Delta Jet | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-07-07-mn-22011-story.html | agency=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=July 7, 1996 | url-access=subscription | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161534/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-07-07-mn-22011-story.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|July 6, 1996\n|MD-88\n|[[Pensacola International Airport|Pensacola]]\n|An uncontained engine failure of the port (left) engine on the aircraft resulted in a fan hub piercing the cabin. The flight was scheduled to fly to Atlanta. The aircraft involved in this accident, N927DA, was repaired and returned to service. The aircraft was eventually retired on August 10, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.planespotters.net/airframe/McDonnell-Douglas/MD-80/N927DA-Delta-Air-Lines/JqnGIaOp | title=N927DA Delta Air Lines McDonnell Douglas MD-88 | website=www.planespotters.net | access-date=August 21, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821223127/https://www.planespotters.net/airframe/McDonnell-Douglas/MD-80/N927DA-Delta-Air-Lines/JqnGIaOp | archive-date=August 21, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|2\n|2\n|3\n|135\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 1989|1989]]<ref name=\"gray\">{{cite web | url=http://www.historycommons.org/context.jsp?item=a942deltaorders | title=Delta Air Lines Tells Flight 1989 to Land at Cleveland Airport, but FAA Not Informed | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606175854/http://historycommons.org/context.jsp?item=a942deltaorders | archive-date=June 6, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=911report>{{cite web | url=https://www.9-11commission.gov/report/ | title=The 9/11 Commission Report | isbn=0-16-072304-3 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718045018/https://9-11commission.gov/report/ | archive-date=July 18, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|[[September 11 2001|September 11, 2001]]\n|[[Boeing 767]]-300\n|En route from [[Boston Logan International Airport|Boston]]\n|Flight 1989, bound for Los Angeles International Airport was caught in the path of [[United Airlines Flight 93]]. The two aircraft were so close that ATC were initially confused as to which plane had been hijacked. The Delta pilot managed to avoid [[United Airlines Flight 93|United 93]] and the flight was later diverted to [[Cleveland Hopkins International Airport]].<ref name=911report/>\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|All\n|0\n|-\n|129<ref>{{cite web |title=ASN Wikibase Occurrence # 173898 |url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=173898 |website=Aviation Safety Network |access-date=February 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206103931/https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=173898 |archive-date=February 6, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|February 3, 2002\n|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-11]]\n|[[Dublin Airport|Dublin]]\n|Flight 129 from Atlanta skidded off the runway at Dublin Airport in high winds. The port engine of MD-11 N803DE had severe damage.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.airliners.net/photo/Delta-Air-Lines/McDonnell-Douglas-MD-11/217135 | title=McDonnell Douglas MD-11 - Delta Airlines | publisher=Airliners.net | date=February 3, 2002 | access-date=February 5, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206103559/http://www.airliners.net/photo/Delta-Air-Lines/McDonnell-Douglas-MD-11/217135 | archive-date=February 6, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|All\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 1086|1086]]\n|March 5, 2015\n|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-88]]\n|[[LaGuardia Airport]]\n|While landing in heavy snowfall, Flight 1086 from Atlanta departed the left side of runway while traveling approximately {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}}, coming to rest nearly perpendicular to the runway with its nose on an embankment beside the waters of [[Flushing Bay]]. The accident resulted in damage to the aircraft's left wing (including a fuel leak<!-- from the left wing's fuel tank -->), nose landing gear well, main electronics bay, nose radome/weather radar, and undercarriage damage forward of the front doors. The aircraft's braking system and condition of the runway surface are being considered as possible causes of the incident.<ref>{{cite news | last=Pasztor | first1=Andy | title=Delta Crash: Investigators Suspect Possible Brake Problems | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-crash-investigators-suspect-possible-brake-problems-1425852167 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=March 9, 2015 | url-access=subscription | access-date=March 6, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709135222/https://www.wsj.com/articles/delta-crash-investigators-suspect-possible-brake-problems-1425852167 | archive-date=July 9, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=NTSB Issues Second Update on the Delta Flight 1086 Accident at LaGuardia| url=http://www.ntsb.gov/news/press-releases/Pages/PR20150309.aspx| publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]| date=March 9, 2015| access-date=March 12, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311151945/http://www.ntsb.gov/news/press-releases/Pages/PR20150309.aspx| archive-date=March 11, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref>\n|0\n|0\n|23<!-- NTSB second update (March 9, 2015): \"Twenty three passengers received minor injuries, and others were transported to the hospital for evaluation. All passengers have been released from the hospital.\" -->\n|109<!-- NTSB second update (March 9, 2015): \"There were 127 passengers (including 2 lap children) and 5 crewmembers on board the flight.\" 127 (pax) +5 (crew) - 23 (minor injuries) = 109 -->\n|0\n|-\n|159\n|June 16, 2015\n|[[Boeing 747]]-400\n|Over Chinese [[airspace]]\n|Flight 159 from Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport to [[Seoul]], [[Incheon International Airport]] was over Chinese airspace when the aircraft flew through a severe hailstorm. This resulted in substantial damage to the aircraft's radome (hail penetrating nose causing a large hole) as well as leading edges of the wing destroyed and damage to the tail plane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=48893f03&opt=0|title=The Aviation Herald|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacdec.de/2015/06/30/2015-06-17-delta-boeing-747-400-badly-damaged-by-hail-over-china/|title=2015-06-17 Delta Boeing 747-400 badly damaged by hail over China|publisher=|access-date=June 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710075650/http://www.jacdec.de/2015/06/30/2015-06-17-delta-boeing-747-400-badly-damaged-by-hail-over-china/|archive-date=July 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> This aircraft was written off due to its age and because Delta had already began retiring its Boeing 747-400 fleet.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://savvystews.com/2015/06/delta-747-possibly-destroyed-by-hail-on-detroit-to-seoul-flight/ | title=Delta 747 Destroyed By Hail, Aircraft a Total Loss | work=SavvyStews.com | access-date=June 30, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702074426/http://savvystews.com/2015/06/delta-747-possibly-destroyed-by-hail-on-detroit-to-seoul-flight | archive-date=July 2, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> Temporary repairs were made (to make it airworthy) and the aircraft was ferried from Seoul to [[Pinal Airpark]] in Marana, Arizona.\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|All\n|0\n|-\n|[[Delta Air Lines Flight 89|89]]\n|January 14, 2020\n|[[Boeing 777-200]]\n|[[South Los Angeles]]\n|Flight 89 from [[Los Angeles International Airport]] to [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport]] reported a problem when one of its engines experienced a [[compressor stall]] shortly after takeoff. The plane turned back and dumped fuel over a five-mile portion of the Los Angeles county area, causing 56 injuries on the ground.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bakersfield.com/ap/news/jet-dumps-fuel-that-lands-on-schoolkids-near-los-angeles/article_c5294eb9-dc16-5e02-9b94-351f3fdbe26f.html |title=Jet dumps fuel that lands on schoolkids near Los Angeles |last=Dazio |first=Stefanie |date=January 14, 2020|website=The Bakersfield Californian| access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> The plane made a safe emergency landing at LAX with no injuries.\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|All\n|56\n|}\n\n*The attempted bombing of [[Northwest Airlines Flight 253]] on December 25, 2009, occurred four days before the operating certificates of Northwest and Delta were combined (December 31, 2009). The aircraft involved in the incident was in Delta livery and reported in some early news reports as \"Delta Flight 253.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Harry|title=Delta's Flight 253 Passengers Get Travel Vouchers From Delta After Foiled Terror Plot|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/30/deltas-flight-253-passeng_n_407196.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102081758/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/30/deltas-flight-253-passeng_n_407196.html|archivedate=January 2, 2010 | publisher=[[HuffPost]] | agency=[[Associated Press]] | date=March 18, 2010}}</ref><!-- Examples:\n*http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/30/deltas-flight-253-passeng_n_407196.html (an AP article)\n*http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/terror-attacks-attempts-since-9-11/21/\n*http://blog.seattlepi.com/airlinereporter/2010/03/09/test-shows-delta-flight-253-could-have-safely-landed-even-if-bomb-detonated/\n*http://www.news.com.au/world/man-arrested-on-flight-into-detroit/story-e6frfkyi-1225814037084\n*https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/12/25/usa-flight-incident-idUSN2513989920091225\n*http://www.sanfranciscosentinel.com/?p=53948\nFurthermore, a ruling about the bomber's statements to investigators uses the term \"Northwest-Delta Flight 253\":\n*http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/USCOURTS-mied-2_10-cr-20005/pdf/USCOURTS-mied-2_10-cr-20005-3.pdf\n-->\n\n===Hijackings===\nThere have been over a dozen attempted hijackings that resulted in no injuries and the surrender of the often lone hijacker. These incidents are not included. The following are notable hijackings because of fatalities or success in forcing the aircraft to fly to another country:\n* On February 21, 1968, a Delta DC-8 was hijacked to Havana, Cuba. This was the first successful hijacking to Cuba from the U.S. since 1961,{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} and was the start of multiple hijacking attempts to Cuba in the late 1960s. This coincided with the introduction of passenger screening using metal detectors in U.S. airports starting in the late 1960s.\n* On July 31, 1972, [[Delta Flight 841]], a Detroit to Miami DC-8 flight, was hijacked to [[Algiers, Algeria]] by 8 hijackers. The aircraft stopped in Boston to pick up an international navigator. The flight was allowed to return with passengers to the U.S., stopping in Barcelona for refueling.<ref name=\"nbc\">{{cite news|url=http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=465514|title=Delta Hijacking|work=[[NBC Nightly News]]|publisher=Vanderbilt Television News Archive|date=August 1, 1972|accessdate=January 31, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010051353/http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=465514|archive-date=October 10, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19720731-0&lang=en|title=ASN Aircraft accident McDonnell Douglas DC-8 Algiers|publisher=Aviation-safety.net|accessdate=March 1, 2009|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66UDVH6K1?url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19720731-0|archive-date=March 27, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On February 22, 1974, [[Samuel Byck]], an unemployed tire salesman from Pennsylvania, shot and killed an Aviation Police Officer, then stormed aboard [[Delta Air Lines Flight 523]], a McDonnell Douglas DC-9 flight at Baltimore Friendship Airport (now [[Baltimore\u2013Washington International Airport]]) scheduled to fly to Atlanta, and shot both pilots, killing the First Officer, Fred Jones. He intended to crash the plane into the [[White House]].<ref name=\"schneier\">{{cite web |url=http://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2006/06/patrick_smith_o.html |title=Patrick Smith on Airline Security |work=Schneier on Security |publisher=Schneier.com |date=June 19, 2006 |accessdate=January 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66UDVsqzW?url=http://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2006/06/patrick_smith_o.html |archive-date=March 27, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> After shooting the pilots, the hijacker grabbed a passenger and demanded that she fly the aircraft.<ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite web| url=http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=233047| title=Hijack Attempt| work=[[CBS Evening News]]| publisher=Vanderbilt Television News Archive| date=February 22, 1974| access-date=May 11, 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321165624/http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=233047| archive-date=March 21, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> The passengers meanwhile fled the aircraft. The hijacking attempt ended when, after a standoff with police, Byck was shot twice through an aircraft porthole by a Maryland policeman, severely wounding him. Before police stormed the plane, Byck killed himself. The plane never left the gate during this incident.\n* On August 23, 1980, a Delta Air Lines L-1011 on a San Juan to Los Angeles flight was hijacked and flown to Cuba.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news | url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,948993,00.html | title=CUBA: Havana-Bound | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=August 25, 1980 | url-access=subscription | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161532/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,948993,00.html | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The hijacker was jailed by Cuban authorities, and all passengers were released unharmed.\n* On September 13, 1980, a Delta Air Lines New Orleans to Atlanta flight was taken over by two hijackers and forced to fly to Cuba. The flight continued to Atlanta after stopping in Havana. The hijackers were imprisoned by Cuban authorities. One hijacker was released and later sought US residency. The suspect was later arrested by US authorities in 2002<ref name=\"diaz\">{{cite news| url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-2002-08-17-0208170049-story.html | title=Tip Yields Arrest Of Hijack Suspect| work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] | first= Madeline BarM-s | last=Diaz | date=August 17, 2002}}</ref> and sentenced to 10 years in prison the following year.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.michigansthumb.com/news/article/Cuban-Man-Gets-10-Years-for-Hijacking-7358645.php | title=Cuban Man Gets 10 Years for Hijacking | work=[[Huron Daily Tribune]] | date=March 11, 2003 | access-date=July 27, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721014954/https://www.michigansthumb.com/news/article/Cuban-Man-Gets-10-Years-for-Hijacking-7358645.php | archive-date=July 21, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Additional hijackings that resulted in no injuries and the flight landing in Cuba include March 28, 1984 (Delta 357, a 727, New Orleans-Dallas),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19840328-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 727 registration unknown Havana-Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ed International Airport (HAV)|website=Aviation-safety.net|date=March 28, 1984|accessdate=March 1, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050909212615/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19840328-0|archive-date=September 9, 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> August 18, 1983 (Delta 784, a 727, Miami-Tampa),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19830818-0 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 727 registration unknown Havana-Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ed International Airport (HAV) |website=Aviation-safety.net |date= |accessdate=March 1, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105203437/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19830818-0 |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> July 17, 1983 (Delta 722, a 727, Miami-Tampa),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19830717-0 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 727 registration unknown Havana-Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ed International Airport (HAV) |website=Aviation-safety.net |date= |accessdate=March 1, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105203414/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19830717-0 |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and June 11, 1979 (Delta 1061, a L-1011, New York LaGuardia-Fort Lauderdale).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19790611-1 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Lockheed L-1011 TriStar registration unknown Havana |website=Aviation-safety.net |date= |accessdate=March 1, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050905192856/http://www.aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19790611-1 |archive-date=September 5, 2005 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Delta Air Lines}}\n{{Portal|Companies|Aviation}}\n* [[Air transportation in the United States]]\n* [[Delta Flight Museum]]\n* [[Delta Global Staffing]]\n* [[List of airlines of the United States]]\n* [[List of airports in the United States]]\n* [[Transportation in the United States]]\n* [[Delta Ship 41]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n;Bibliography\n* {{cite book |last1= Green |first1=William | first2=Gordon | last2=Swanborough | first3=John | last3=Mowinski |title= Modern Commercial Aircraft |year= 1987 |publisher=Crown Publishers, Inc. |location=New York |isbn= 0-517-63369-8 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Air travel in the United States}}\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|q=no|s=no|v=no|species=no}}\n* {{official website|https://www.delta.com/|mobile=https://m.delta.com/}}\n* {{OpenCorp}}\n{{Finance links\n| name      = Delta Air Lines\n| google    = DAL\n| yahoo     = DAL\n| bloomberg = DAL:US\n| symbol    = DAL\n| sec_cik   = DAL\n}}\n\n{{Delta Air Lines}}\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Legacy carrier}}\n{{Airline holding companies of the United States}}\n{{SkyTeam}}\n{{IATA members|northam}}\n{{Dow Jones Transportation Average}}\n{{Atlanta companies}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Delta Air Lines| ]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies in the Dow Jones Transportation Average]]\n[[Category:Airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:IATA members]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1928]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1928]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:OpenTravel Alliance]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2005]]\n[[Category:SkyTeam]]\n[[Category:Aviation in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "JuliaWatson", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added a few internal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_Air_Lines"}
{"title_page": "A. E. Ellis (author)", "text_new": "{{for|the British scientist| Arthur Erskine Ellis}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n'''A.E. Ellis''' was the pseudonym used by '''Derek Lindsay''' (1920\u20132000), a British novelist and playwright, to publish his novel, ''The Rack'', and to write two plays, ''Grand Manouevres'' and ''Seagull Rising''. Lindsay/Ellis was orphaned as a child  and served in the British army in [[World War II]]. After the war he went to the [[University of Oxford]] and was diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]] and was treated in a [[sanatorium]] in the [[French Alps]], one of the last people to undergo this form of therapy.\n''The Rack'' is a detailed account of the experience and received high acclaim when it was published in 1958, from [[Graham Greene]] and [[Anthony Burgess]] and others. It was favourably compared with ''[[The Magic Mountain]]'' and has been in print ever since. However, it was the only novel Ellis published. \nAlthough there was said to be  an unpublished novel left after his death, this has never appeared, although a \"restored edition\" of ''The Rack'', with passages removed from the first edition by its editor, [[James Michie]], re-inserted, has been published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashgrovepublishinglondon.com/backlist/|title=Zephyr Books|website=ashgrovepublishing}}</ref>\nHe also wrote at least two plays. ''Grand Manouevres'', about the [[Dreyfus Affair]], was produced at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in 1974 and received a hostile reception, while ''Seagull Rising'', inspired by [[Chekhov]], was put on at [[The Questors Theatre]] in 1977.\nHe was described as \"saturnine and reclusive\", but had many friends, including [[Graham Greene]], who compared ''The Rack'' with ''[[Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]'' in importance,  [[Kenneth Tynan]] and [[Andrew Sinclair]], who both wrote about him and [[Cyril Connolly]]. He had a son, Timon, with Marianne Sinclair, Andrew Sinclair's first wife.\n\n==Notes==\n*[[Alan Wall]]: introduction to [[Zephyr Books]] edition of ''The Rack''.\n*[[Andrew Sinclair]]: introduction to [[Valancourt Books]] edition of ''The Rack''.\n*[[Andrew Sinclair]]: London Magazine, Volume 41, Issues 1-2. 2001\n*{{cite journal |last=Meyers |first=Jeffrey |author-link=Jeffrey Meyers|title=A. E. Ellis and ''The Rack'': An Unpublished Letter |journal=Style |date=2019 |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=79 |doi=10.5325/style.53.1.0079}}\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, A. E.}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{for|the British scientist| Arthur Erskine Ellis}}\n'''A.E. Ellis''' was the pseudonym used by '''Derek Lindsay''' (1920\u20132000), a British novelist and playwright, to publish his novel, ''The Rack'', and to write two plays, ''Grand Manouevres'' and ''Seagull Rising''. Lindsay/Ellis was orphaned as a child  and served in the British army in [[World War II]]. After the war he went to the [[Univerity  of Oxford]] and was diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]] and was treated in a [[sanatorium]] in the [[French Alps]], one of the last people to undergo this form of therapy.\n''The Rack'' is a detailed account of the experience and received high acclaim when it was published in 1958, from [[Graham Greene]] and [[Anthony Burgess]] and others. It was favourably compared with ''[[The Magic Mountain]]'' and has been in print ever since. However, it was the only novel Ellis published. \nAlthough there was said to be  an unpublished novel left after his death, this has never appeared, although a \"restored edition\" of ''The Rack'', with passages removed from the first edition by its editor, [[James Michie]], re-inserted, has been published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashgrovepublishinglondon.com/backlist/|title=Zephyr Books|website=ashgrovepublishing}}</ref>\nHe also wrote at least two plays. ''Grand Manouevres'', about the [[Dreyfus Affair]], was produced at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in 1974 and received a hostile reception, while ''Seagull Rising'', inspired by [[Chekhov]], was put on at [[The Questors Theatre]] in 1977.\nHe was described as \"saturnine and reclusive\", but had many friends, including [[Graham Greene]], who compared ''The Rack'' with ''[[Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]'' in importance,  [[Kenneth Tynan]] and [[Andrew Sinclair]], who both wrote about him and [[Cyril Connolly]]. He had a son, Timon, with Marianne Sinclair, Andrew Sinclair's first wife.\n\n==Notes==\n*[[Alan Wall]]: introduction to [[Zephyr Books]] edition of ''The Rack''.\n*[[Andrew Sinclair]]: introduction to [[Valancourt Books]] edition of ''The Rack''.\n*[[Andrew Sinclair]]: London Magazine, Volume 41, Issues 1-2. 2001\n*{{cite journal |last=Meyers |first=Jeffrey |author-link=Jeffrey Meyers|title=A. E. Ellis and ''The Rack'': An Unpublished Letter |journal=Style |date=2019 |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=79 |doi=10.5325/style.53.1.0079}}\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, A. E.}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Univerity \u2192 University", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._E._Ellis_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Supply chain risk management", "text_new": "[[File:Supply and demand network (en).png|thumb|400px|Supply-chain risk management is aimed at managing risks in complex and dynamic supply and demand networks.<ref name=\"Wieland-Wallenburg\">cf. Andreas Wieland, Carl Marcus Wallenburg (2011): ''Supply-Chain-Management in st\u00fcrmischen Zeiten''. Berlin.</ref> (cf. Wieland/Wallenburg, 2011)]]\n\n'''Supply-chain risk management''' (SCRM) is \"the implementation of strategies to manage both everyday and exceptional risks along the [[supply chain]] based on continuous risk assessment with the objective of reducing vulnerability and ensuring continuity\".<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1108/09600031211281411| title=A Critical Review on Supply Chain Risk \u2013 Definition, Measure and Modeling| journal=Omega| volume=52| issue=April 2015| pages=119-132| year=2015| last1=Heckmann| first1=Iris | last2=Comes| first2=Tina | last3=Nickel| first3=Stefan| url=https://depositonce.tu-berlin.de//handle/11303/7030}}</ref>\n\nThe assessment of supply chain risk is closely related to the objectives that need to be accomplished by the underlying supply chain. The degree of achievement of these objectives depends on the exposition of the underlying supply\nchain towards unexpected and uncertain developments. Risk exposition is further classified by potentially disrupting triggers, supply chain\u2019s ability to handle irritations, and time-based aspects that align the occurrence of the disruptive triggers to the current status of the supply chain. The significance of a potential non-achievement of objectives is\nassessed by the risk attitude of the decision-maker. <ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.omega.2014.10.004| title=Dealing with supply chain risks| journal=International Journal of Physical Distribution & Logistics Management| volume=42| issue=10| pages=887\u2013905| year=2012| last1=Wieland| first1=Andreas| last2=Marcus Wallenburg| first2=Carl| url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.omega.2014.10.004}}</ref>\n\nIn other words, SCRM is to apply risk management process tools, with partners in a supply chain or on your own, to deal with risks and uncertainties caused by, or affecting, logistics-related activities or resources in the supply chain.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Supply Chain Risk|last=Brindley|first=Clare|publisher=Ashgate Publishing Ltd.|year=2004|isbn=0754639029|location=England|pages=80}}</ref>\n\n== Supply-chain exposures ==\nSCRM attempts to reduce supply-chain vulnerability via a coordinated holistic approach, involving all supply-chain stakeholders, which identifies and analyzes the risk of failure points within the supply chain. Risks to the supply chain range from unpredictable natural threats to counterfeit products, and reach across quality, security, to resiliency and product integrity. Mitigation plans to manage these risks can involve logistics, cybersecurity, finance and risk management disciplines; the ultimate goal being to ensure supply chain continuity in the event of a scenario which otherwise would have interrupted normal business and so profitability.\n\nSometimes, it's possible for supply chain logistics techniques such as [[Supply_chain_optimization|supply-chain optimization]] to prejudice contingency planning which would otherwise reduce the overall risk level for that particular supply chain. It is also becoming more common among businesses especially manufacturers to employ a supplier quality management software, which integrates all phases of the supply-chain cycle. This approach is shown to increase transparency, reduce overhead costs, and improve operational efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|title=Managing the Supply Chain with Quality Management Software|url=http://www.slideshare.net/spartasystems/managing-the-supply-chain-with-trackwise|publisher=Sparta Systems|accessdate=27 July 2015|date=2015-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Resilience ==\n\nSupply chain risk management typically involves four processes: identification, assessment, controlling, and monitoring of supply-chain risks.<ref>Wieland & Wallenburg (2012)</ref> However, due to the complexity of many supply chains, these processes might not be sufficient to ensure that all eventualities are prepared for. Therefore, the concept of supply-chain risk management, which is cause-oriented, is often combined with the concept of supply-chain resilience, which aims to ensure that the supply chain can bounce back from risks irrespective of their cause. Supply chain resilience is therefore \"The adaptive capability of the supply chain to prepare for unexpected events, respond to\ndisruptions, and recover from them by maintaining continuity of operations at the desired level of connectedness and control over structure and function\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ponomarov |first1=Serhiy Y. |last2=Holcomb |first2=Mary C. |title=Understanding the concept of supply chain resilience |journal=International Journal of Logistics Management |date=2009 |volume=20 |issue=1 |page=124\u2013143 |doi=10.1108/09574090910954873}}</ref>\n\n== Time to recover ==\nAn important metric originally introduced by Cisco and adopted by the SCRLC is called \"time to recover\" (TTR<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scrlc.com/newsletter-readMore.php?aID=132|title=SCRLC|website=www.scrlc.com|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>).  TTR is the time it takes a company to restore 100% of operational output following a major supply-chain disruption.  The determination of TTR assumes that the facility is essentially unusable due to a major event, and would need extensive repairs and reconstruction, as well as re-sourcing and re-qualifying of key equipment used in manufacturing and other operations.\n\n== Measuring risk ==\nSupply-chain risk is a function of likelihood of an event's occurrence and its impact.  Generally this is the most popular methodology for quantifying risk.  The drawback of using this to compute supply-chain risk, is that it requires assessing likelihood or probability of many different event types for n number of supply-chain locations (which can be hundreds of thousands of locations).  Thus, the range of different possibilities is very wide.  This methodology is generally more appropriate for a smaller subset of site(s).  Most companies look at measuring risk using risk scores.  Many different metrics are available.  For example, financial risk score, operational risk score, resiliency score (R Score), etc. are easily acquired, easily analyzed and can be used effectively and understood easily.\n\n== Managing risk proactively ==\nA survey in 2011 conducted by BCI and Zurich for over 559 companies across 65 countries found that over 85% of companies had suffered at least one supply-chain disruption during the year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20111102/NEWS06/111109973/Majority-of-companies-suffered-supply-chain-disruption-in-2011-Survey|title=Majority of companies suffered supply-chain disruption in 2011: Survey - Business Insurance|work=Business Insurance|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>  The respondents also noted that 40% of the reported disruptions originated in a sub-tier supplier and not their direct supplier.\n\n== Contingency options ==\nSome options to engineer an acceptable risk level include:\n*Managing stock\n*Considering alternative sourcing arrangements\n*Business interruption / contingency insurance\n*Risk assessments and audits\n*Awareness campaigns and training programs\n*The use of business intelligence from big data analytics and continuous monitoring for predictive security measures vs. clean up\n*Redundancy optimization\n*Postponement\n*Collaboration<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tang|first=Christopher S.|date=2006|title=Robust strategies for mitigating supply chain disruptions.|url=|journal=International Journal of Logistics Research and Applications |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201345|doi=10.1080/13675560500405584|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Supply-chain security]]\n* [[Cybersecurity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Books==\n* Choi, T.M., C.H. Chiu. Risk Analysis in Stochastic Supply Chains: A Mean-Risk Approach, Springer, International Series in Operations Research and Management Science, 2012.\n* Brindley, Clare. 2004. ''Supply Chain Risk''. Ashgate Publishing Ltd., England, Ed. 1.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110817205640/http://www.weforum.org/content/pages/supply-chain-and-transport-risk-initiative World Economic Forum Supply Chain and Transport Risk Initiative]\n\n[[Category:Supply chain management]]\n[[Category:Risk management in business]]\n[[Category:Operational risk]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Supply and demand network (en).png|thumb|400px|Supply-chain risk management is aimed at managing risks in complex and dynamic supply and demand networks.<ref name=\"Wieland-Wallenburg\">cf. Andreas Wieland, Carl Marcus Wallenburg (2011): ''Supply-Chain-Management in st\u00fcrmischen Zeiten''. Berlin.</ref> (cf. Wieland/Wallenburg, 2011)]]\n\n'''Supply-chain risk management''' (SCRM) is \"the implementation of strategies to manage both everyday and exceptional risks along the [[supply chain]] based on continuous risk assessment with the objective of reducing vulnerability and ensuring continuity\".<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1108/09600031211281411| title=A Critical Review on Supply Chain Risk \u2013\nDefinition, Measure and Modeling| journal=Omega| volume=52| issue=April 2015| pages=119-132| year=2015| last1=Heckmann| first1=Iris | last2=Comes| first2=Tina | last3=Nickel| first3=Stefan| url=https://depositonce.tu-berlin.de//handle/11303/7030}}</ref>\n\nThe assessment of supply chain risk is closely related to the objectives that need to be accomplished by the underlying supply chain. The degree of achievement of these objectives depends on the exposition of the underlying supply\nchain towards unexpected and uncertain developments. Risk exposition is further classified by potentially disrupting triggers, supply chain\u2019s ability to handle irritations, and time-based aspects that align the occurrence of the disruptive triggers to the current status of the supply chain. The significance of a potential non-achievement of objectives is\nassessed by the risk attitude of the decision-maker. <ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.omega.2014.10.004| title=Dealing with supply chain risks| journal=International Journal of Physical Distribution & Logistics Management| volume=42| issue=10| pages=887\u2013905| year=2012| last1=Wieland| first1=Andreas| last2=Marcus Wallenburg| first2=Carl| url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.omega.2014.10.004}}</ref>\n\nIn other words, SCRM is to apply risk management process tools, with partners in a supply chain or on your own, to deal with risks and uncertainties caused by, or affecting, logistics-related activities or resources in the supply chain.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Supply Chain Risk|last=Brindley|first=Clare|publisher=Ashgate Publishing Ltd.|year=2004|isbn=0754639029|location=England|pages=80}}</ref>\n\n== Supply-chain exposures ==\nSCRM attempts to reduce supply-chain vulnerability via a coordinated holistic approach, involving all supply-chain stakeholders, which identifies and analyzes the risk of failure points within the supply chain. Risks to the supply chain range from unpredictable natural threats to counterfeit products, and reach across quality, security, to resiliency and product integrity. Mitigation plans to manage these risks can involve logistics, cybersecurity, finance and risk management disciplines; the ultimate goal being to ensure supply chain continuity in the event of a scenario which otherwise would have interrupted normal business and so profitability.\n\nSometimes, it's possible for supply chain logistics techniques such as [[Supply_chain_optimization|supply-chain optimization]] to prejudice contingency planning which would otherwise reduce the overall risk level for that particular supply chain. It is also becoming more common among businesses especially manufacturers to employ a supplier quality management software, which integrates all phases of the supply-chain cycle. This approach is shown to increase transparency, reduce overhead costs, and improve operational efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|title=Managing the Supply Chain with Quality Management Software|url=http://www.slideshare.net/spartasystems/managing-the-supply-chain-with-trackwise|publisher=Sparta Systems|accessdate=27 July 2015|date=2015-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Resilience ==\n\nSupply chain risk management typically involves four processes: identification, assessment, controlling, and monitoring of supply-chain risks.<ref>Wieland & Wallenburg (2012)</ref> However, due to the complexity of many supply chains, these processes might not be sufficient to ensure that all eventualities are prepared for. Therefore, the concept of supply-chain risk management, which is cause-oriented, is often combined with the concept of supply-chain resilience, which aims to ensure that the supply chain can bounce back from risks irrespective of their cause. Supply chain resilience is therefore \"The adaptive capability of the supply chain to prepare for unexpected events, respond to\ndisruptions, and recover from them by maintaining continuity of operations at the desired level of connectedness and control over structure and function\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ponomarov |first1=Serhiy Y. |last2=Holcomb |first2=Mary C. |title=Understanding the concept of supply chain resilience |journal=International Journal of Logistics Management |date=2009 |volume=20 |issue=1 |page=124\u2013143 |doi=10.1108/09574090910954873}}</ref>\n\n== Time to recover ==\nAn important metric originally introduced by Cisco and adopted by the SCRLC is called \"time to recover\" (TTR<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scrlc.com/newsletter-readMore.php?aID=132|title=SCRLC|website=www.scrlc.com|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>).  TTR is the time it takes a company to restore 100% of operational output following a major supply-chain disruption.  The determination of TTR assumes that the facility is essentially unusable due to a major event, and would need extensive repairs and reconstruction, as well as re-sourcing and re-qualifying of key equipment used in manufacturing and other operations.\n\n== Measuring risk ==\nSupply-chain risk is a function of likelihood of an event's occurrence and its impact.  Generally this is the most popular methodology for quantifying risk.  The drawback of using this to compute supply-chain risk, is that it requires assessing likelihood or probability of many different event types for n number of supply-chain locations (which can be hundreds of thousands of locations).  Thus, the range of different possibilities is very wide.  This methodology is generally more appropriate for a smaller subset of site(s).  Most companies look at measuring risk using risk scores.  Many different metrics are available.  For example, financial risk score, operational risk score, resiliency score (R Score), etc. are easily acquired, easily analyzed and can be used effectively and understood easily.\n\n== Managing risk proactively ==\nA survey in 2011 conducted by BCI and Zurich for over 559 companies across 65 countries found that over 85% of companies had suffered at least one supply-chain disruption during the year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20111102/NEWS06/111109973/Majority-of-companies-suffered-supply-chain-disruption-in-2011-Survey|title=Majority of companies suffered supply-chain disruption in 2011: Survey - Business Insurance|work=Business Insurance|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>  The respondents also noted that 40% of the reported disruptions originated in a sub-tier supplier and not their direct supplier.\n\n== Contingency options ==\nSome options to engineer an acceptable risk level include:\n*Managing stock\n*Considering alternative sourcing arrangements\n*Business interruption / contingency insurance\n*Risk assessments and audits\n*Awareness campaigns and training programs\n*The use of business intelligence from big data analytics and continuous monitoring for predictive security measures vs. clean up\n*Redundancy optimization\n*Postponement\n*Collaboration<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tang|first=Christopher S.|date=2006|title=Robust strategies for mitigating supply chain disruptions.|url=|journal=International Journal of Logistics Research and Applications |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201345|doi=10.1080/13675560500405584|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Supply-chain security]]\n* [[Cybersecurity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Books==\n* Choi, T.M., C.H. Chiu. Risk Analysis in Stochastic Supply Chains: A Mean-Risk Approach, Springer, International Series in Operations Research and Management Science, 2012.\n* Brindley, Clare. 2004. ''Supply Chain Risk''. Ashgate Publishing Ltd., England, Ed. 1.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110817205640/http://www.weforum.org/content/pages/supply-chain-and-transport-risk-initiative World Economic Forum Supply Chain and Transport Risk Initiative]\n\n[[Category:Supply chain management]]\n[[Category:Risk management in business]]\n[[Category:Operational risk]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supply_chain_risk_management"}
